e for the expected peak impact.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\n====March 14====\n\nThe total US cases passed 2,700. Five additional deaths were reported by state health departments: three in Washington, one in Florida, and one in Louisiana. In addition, New York's first death was reported in the news media and the governor of New Jersey announced the state's second death on Twitter. This brought reported deaths to 7{{nbsp}}for the day.\n* North Carolina: All schools ordered to close for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-roy-cooper-orders-nc-schools-close-least-weeks/ |title=Gov. Roy Cooper orders NC schools to close for at least 2 weeks |last=Lawson |first=Adam |date=March 14, 2020 |website=[[WBTV]] |language=en-US |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315050920/https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-roy-cooper-orders-nc-schools-close-least-weeks/ |archive-date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Governor Roy Cooper also issued an executive order to prevent mass gathering.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wbtv.com/2020/03/14/gov-cooper-issues-executive-order-stop-mass-gatherings-nc/ |title=Gov. Cooper issues executive order to stop mass gatherings in NC |website=wbtv.com |publisher=WBTV Web |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n* Ohio: Governor Mike DeWine and Department of Health Director [[Amy Acton]] on March 14 recommended Ohioans postpone elective surgeries.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/ohioans-should-postpone-many-elective-surgeries-because-of-coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-recommends.html |title=Ohioans should postpone many elective surgeries because of the coronavirus, Gov. Mike DeWine recommends |last=Pelzer |first=Jeremy |last2=clevel |date=2020-03-14 |website=cleveland |language=en |access-date=2020-03-16 |last3=.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316155149/https://www.cleveland.com/open/2020/03/ohioans-should-postpone-many-elective-surgeries-because-of-coronavirus-gov-mike-dewine-recommends.html |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Oklahoma: Governor [[Kevin Stitt]] took a selfie with his family in a crowded restaurant. Stitt tweeted, \"It's packed tonight!\" and was criticized on social media for ignoring social distancing. Stitt deleted the tweet in response to the backlash.<ref>[https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/487811-states-lead-unevenly-on-coronavirus-response States lead, unevenly, on coronavirus response] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317165312/https://thehill.com/homenews/state-watch/487811-states-lead-unevenly-on-coronavirus-response |date=March 17, 2020 }} The Hill, 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n* Virginia: Governor [[Ralph Northam]] announced Virginia's first death from the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/14/virginia-first-coronavirus-death-129597 |title=Virginia governor announces state's first death from coronavirus |last=Semones |first=Evan |website=POLITICO |language=en |access-date=2020-03-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317060801/https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/14/virginia-first-coronavirus-death-129597 |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====March 15====\n\nOn March 15, the CDC issued guidance recommending against any gathering of 50 or more people for an eight-week period.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/cdc-recommends-the-cancellation-of-events-with-50-or-more-people-for-the-next-eight-weeks-throughout-us.html |title=CDC recommends canceling events with 50 or more people for the next eight weeks throughout US |last=Kopecki |first=Dawn |date=2020-03-15 |website=CNBC |language=en |access-date=2020-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318180317/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/16/cdc-recommends-the-cancellation-of-events-with-50-or-more-people-for-the-next-eight-weeks-throughout-us.html |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Alabama: The Alabama Department of Public Health counted 22 cases of coronavirus: Jefferson County, 12 cases; Tuscaloosa County, 3{{nbsp}}cases; Shelby County, 2{{nbsp}}cases; Baldwin County, Elmore, County, Lee, Limestone, and Montgomery Counties, 1{{nbsp}}case each.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/15/adph-confirmed-cases-coronavirus-alabama-2/ |title=ADPH: 22 confirmed cases of coronavirus in Alabama |date=March 15, 2020 |website=WSFA 12 News |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317072716/https://www.wsfa.com/2020/03/15/adph-confirmed-cases-coronavirus-alabama-2/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Arizona: Governor [[Doug Ducey]] and Superintendent [[Kathy Hoffman]] ordered all schools closed through March 27.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/news/local/arizona-education/2020/03/15/arizona-school-superintendents-aea-teachers-urge-more-action-governor-doug-ducey-lawmakers/5054670002/ |title=Gov. Ducey, Kathy Hoffman: All Arizona schools to close through March 27 |last=Altavena |first=Lily |website=azcentral |language=en |access-date=2020-03-16}}</ref>\n* Connecticut: All schools ordered closed after March 16 until at least March 31.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/gov-lamont-to-give-update-on-coronavirus-in-conn/2239041/|title=Gov. Lamont Issues Executive Order to Close All Schools After Monday|accessdate=Mar 19, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317230546/https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/gov-lamont-to-give-update-on-coronavirus-in-conn/2239041/|archive-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Illinois: Governor [[J.B. Pritzker]] announces that the state will order restaurants and bars to close to dine-in customers.<ref name=\"ILLINOIS OHIO THE HILL RESTAURANTS\">{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487684-illinois-ohio-closing-all-bars-restaurants-in-response-to-coronavirus |title=Illinois, Ohio closing all bars, restaurants in response to coronavirus |last=Conradis |first=Brandon |date=March 15, 2020 |website=thehill.com |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318060255/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/487684-illinois-ohio-closing-all-bars-restaurants-in-response-to-coronavirus |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Maine: Governor [[Janet Mills]] declared a state of emergency in the state with 7{{nbsp}}cases confirmed.<ref name=\":9a\">{{cite web |url=https://bangordailynews.com/2020/03/15/politics/janet-mills-declares-civil-emergency-after-maine-announces-new-coronavirus-cases/ |title=Janet Mills declares state of emergency after Maine announces new coronavirus cases |website=Bangor Daily News |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317231511/https://bangordailynews.com/2020/03/15/politics/janet-mills-declares-civil-emergency-after-maine-announces-new-coronavirus-cases/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Minnesota: Governor Tim Walz closed all schools from March 18 until at least March 27. The state confirmed that there were now 35 confirmed cases of the virus with at least three spread person to person in the state. During the school shutdown meals and mental health services will still be provided to students in need.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-schools-will-close-for-eight-days-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/568812082/?refresh=true |title=Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz closing K-12 schools as COVID-19 spreads |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319210909/http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-schools-will-close-for-eight-days-due-to-coronavirus-pandemic/568812082/?refresh=true |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Under the governor's order, schools will remain open for the elementary-aged children of health care workers and other emergency workers.<ref>{{cite web |u