 U.S., but was very \"China-centric\".<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\n====April 8====\n\n* Georgia: Governor Brian Kemp extends the statewide shelter in place order through the end of April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/breaking-kemp-extends-shelter-place-order-georgia-through-april/TsMutJJldcp9FTb3QTD00J/|title=Kemp extends shelter in place order in Georgia through April|first=Greg|last=Bluestein|website=ajc}}</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increase to 20,346 with a death toll of 959.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 20,346; Death toll now at 959 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/08/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-20346-death-toll-now-at-959/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Minnesota: Governor Tim Walz extends Minnesota's stay at home order until May 4th.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kare11.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/refined-stay-at-home-strategy-for-minnesota/89-3009a986-826f-409a-b54b-260cc1d6939d|title=Walz extends Minnesota's 'Stay at Home' order to May 4|last=|first=|date=April 8, 2020|website=KARE 11|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The number of cases increases to 5,148. Apple CEO Tim Cook donates 100,000 N95 masks to Ohio health care workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/coronavirus/april-8-coronavirus-in-ohio-update|title=Coronavirus cases rise over 5,000 in Ohio with 193 deaths, 1,495 hospitalizations|date=April 8, 2020|website=abc6onyourside.com}}</ref>\n\n====April 9====\n\n* Indiana: The state's amount of coronavirus cases increases to 6,351 with 245 deaths.<ref name=WOM>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/|title=United States Coronavirus: 532,879 Cases and 20,577 Deaths\u2014Worldometer|website=www.worldometers.info}}</ref>\n* Michigan: Gov. Whitmer officially extends the state's stay-at-home order through April 30. It was originally set to expire on the 14th.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Haddad |first1=Ken |title=Michigan extends 'stay home' order to April 30: What you need to know |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/michigan/2020/04/09/michigan-extends-stay-home-order-to-april-30-what-you-need-to-know/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state climb to 21,504 with a death toll of 1,076.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 21,504; Death toll now at 1,076 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/09/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-21504-death-toll-now-at-1076/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The state has more than 5,500 confirmed cases and more than 200 deaths.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/april-9-coronavirus-in-ohio-update|title=Over 5,500 infected with coronavirus in Ohio, deaths rise to 213|date=April 9, 2020|website=abc6onyourside.com}}</ref>\n\n====April 10====\n\n* USA: The 8pm Howl is now sweeping the nation, reports [[The New York Times]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2020/04/10/us/ap-us-virus-outbreak-the-howling.html|title=The Howling: Americans Let It Out From Depths of Pandemic|first=The Associated|last=Press|date=April 10, 2020|via=NYTimes.com}}</ref> It was started in a Denver neighborhood on March 27.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n* Michigan: The field hospital at the [[TCF Center]] in downtown Detroit begins accepting COVID-19 patients.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Spruill |first1=Larry |title=TCF Center becomes fully-functioning field hospital as first coronavirus (COVID-19) patients arrive |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/04/10/tcf-center-becomes-fully-functioning-field-hospital-as-first-coronavirus-covid-19-patients-arrive/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state reach 22,783 with a death toll of 1,281. This represents the largest increase in deaths (205) since the outbreak began in the state.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 22,783; Death toll now at 1,281 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/10/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-22783-death-toll-now-at-1281/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: Governor DeWine announces an emergency amendment to Ohio Department of Medicaid's provider agreement. The new changes are intended to remove barriers to health care and reduce burdens on hospitals and providers. The Food and Drug Administration (FDA) grants STERIS, an Ohio-based company, a temporary Emergency Use Authorization for decontaminating compatible N95 and N95-equivalent respirators. The Ohio Bureau of Workers' Compensation Board of Directors approves a plan to send up to $1.6 billion to Ohio employers in spring of 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.perrycountyohio.net/covid-19-updates/general-covid-19-info/governor-s-office-covid-19-update-april-10-2020|title=Governor's Office COVID-19 Update |date=April 10, 2020|website=perrycountyohio.net}}</ref>\n\n====April 11====\n\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 23,993 with a death toll of 1,392.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dado |first1=Natasha |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 23,993; Death toll now at 1,392 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/11/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-23993-death-toll-now-at-1392/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The number of COVID-19 cases increases to 6,187. The death toll stands at 247.<ref>{{cite web |title=242 confirmed dead in Ohio due to COVID-19; 6,187 confirmed cases statewide |url=https://www.cleveland19.com/2020/04/11/confirmed-dead-ohio-due-covid-confirmed-cases-statewide/|date= April 11, 2020|website=cleveland19.com}}</ref>\n\n====April 12====\n\n* Indiana: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 7,928 with 343 deaths.<ref name=WOM/>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 24,638 with a death toll of 1,487.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dado |first1=Natasha |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 24,638; Death toll now at 1,487 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/11/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-23993-death-toll-now-at-1392/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 13====\n\n* Ohio: Nursing homes are now required to inform families of cases within 24 hours.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fox8.com/news/coronavirus/new-order-requires-ohio-nursing-homes-to-notify-families-of-covid-19-cases/|title=New order requires Ohio nursing homes to notify families of COVID-19 cases|date=April 13, 2020|first=Jen|last=Steer|website=fox8.com}}</ref> Liquor sales are now limited to state residents only in the counties of [[Ashtabula County|Ashtabula]], [[Trumbull County|Trumbull]], [[Mahoning County| Mahoning]], [[Columbiana County| Columbiana]], [[Jefferson County, Ohio| Jefferson]], and [[Belmont County| Belmont]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pittsburgh.cbslocal.com/2020/04/13/ohio-governor-limits-liquor-sales-to-in-state-residents-in-several-ohio-counties/|title=Ohio Governor Limits Liquor Sales To In-State Residents In Several Ohio Counties|date=April 13, 2020|website=cbslocal.com}}</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 25,635 with a death toll of 1,602.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 25,635; Death toll now at 1,602 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/13/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-25635-death-toll-now-at-1697/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 14====\n\nAP reported that: \"Dr. Anthony Fauci, the government's top infectious disease expert, said Tuesday that the U.S. does not yet have the critical testing and tracing procedures needed to begin reopening the nation's economy{{nbsp}}... Fauci said that a May{{nbsp}}1 target is 'a bit overly optimistic' for many areas of the country. Any easing off the strict social-distancing rules in place in much of the country would have to occur on a rolling basis, not all at once.\"<ref name=\"AP_Fauci1\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/46ee40035d500c4190489aea0adb126b|title=Fauci: 'We're not there yet' on key steps to reopen economy|date=April 14, 2020|via=apnews.com}}</ref>\n* Indiana: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 8,527 with 387 deaths.<ref>https://worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/</ref>\n* Ohio: There are 7,280 cases of COVID-19, including 2,156 that resulted in hospitalizations and 324 that resulted in death. Governor DeWine announces that his administration is seeking a Medicaid waiver from the federal government to remove certain healthcare restrictions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abc6onyourside.com/news/local/april-14-coronavirus-in-ohio-update|title=Coronavirus cases rise to 7,280 with 2,156 hospitalizations, 324 deaths|first= Chris|last=White|date=April 14, 2020|website=abc6onyourside.com}}</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 27,001 with a death toll of 1,768.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derek |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 28,059; Death toll now at 1,921 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/15/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-28059-death-toll-now-at-1921/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump announced his decision to halt U.S. funding to the WHO, alleging the U.S. would review alleged mismanagement and cover-up efforts. WHO officials disputed his allegations the following day, saying that: a) the world was alerted January 5th; b) countries globally began to respond January 6; and c) WHO provided updates throughout the period.<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\n====April 15====\n\n* Michigan: A large scale rally called \"Operation Gridlock\" takes place in Lansing to protest Gov. Whitmer's stay-at-home order.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Meloni |first1=Rob |title=Gov. Whitmer stands by stay-at-home order despite large protest in Lansing |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/04/15/gov-whitmer-stands-by-stay-at-home-order-despite-large-protest-in-lansing/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 28,059 with a death toll of 1,921.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 28,059; Death toll now at 1,921 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/15/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-28059-death-toll-now-at-1921/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 16====\n\n* The Trump administration unveils new federal guidelines outlining a three-phased approach to gradually restoring normal commerce and services, with each phase lasting at least 14 days, but only for places with strong testing and seeing a decrease in COVID-19 cases.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/420a38ec14101eab70e07be367ee6422|title=Trump unveils phased approach to reopening economy|date=April 16, 2020|work=Associated Press}}</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 29,263 with a death toll of 2,093.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 29,263; Death toll now at 2,093 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/16/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-29263-death-toll-now-at-2093/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 16, there were 639,664 confirmed coronavirus cases in the U.S., with 30,985 confirmed deaths, a 4.8% mortality rate. An estimated 3.24 million tests had been conducted, indicating about 20% of those tested had coronavirus.<ref name=\"OWID_Apr 16\">{{cite web |url=https://ourworldindata.org/coronavirus#all-charts-preview |title=Coronavirus Disease (COVID-19)\u2014Statistics and Research |website=ourworldindata.org |accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Atlantic_20pct\">{{cite web |title=A New Statistic Reveals Why America's COVID-19 Numbers Are Flat |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2020/04/us-coronavirus-outbreak-out-control-test-positivity-rate/610132/ |website=theatlantic.com|date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 17====\n\n* Indiana: For the 1st time, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state surpasses 10,000 (10,154) with the death toll increasing to 519.<ref>https://worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/</ref> Also Governor [[Eric Holcomb]] extends the stay-at-home order until May 1.<ref>https://wthitv.com/content/news/Indiana-Governor-Eric-Holcomb-to-extend-states-stay-at-home-order-until-May-1-569734211.html</ref>\n* Michigan: Detroit mayor [[Mike Duggan]] announces that all essential workers in the city, regardless of whether they exhibit symptoms or not, are now eligible to be tested for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mann |first1=Priya |title=All essential Detroit employees now eligible to be tested for coronavirus (COVID-19) |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/news/local/2020/04/17/all-essential-detroit-employees-now-eligible-to-be-tested-for-coronavirus-covid-19/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, the total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 30,023 with a death toll of 2,227.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 30,023; Death toll now at 2,227 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/17/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-30023-death-toll-now-at-2227/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Texas: State governor G. Abbott announced a phased reopening of Texas' economy beginning April 20th.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Rapaport-Prendergast-Glynn-Clark |first1=Wes-Matthew-Maggie-Kevin |title=Gov. Abbott announces phased reopening of Texas businesses|url=https://www.https://www.kxan.com/news/coronavirus/gov-abbott-reveals-plan-to-reopen-texas-economy/ |website=www.kxan.com |accessdate=18 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 18====\n\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 30,791 with a death toll of 2,308.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dado |first1=Natasha |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 30,791; Death toll now at 2,308 with 3,237 recoveries reported |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/18/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-30791-death-toll-now-at-2-308-with-3237-recoveries/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Indiana: Dozens protest outside of the Governors mansion in Indianapolis after the issue of the latest stay-at-home order; this despite the number of cases in the state continuing to go up.<ref>https://www.wishtv.com/news/indiana-news/dozens-protest-indiana-stay-at-home-order-outside-governors-mansion/</ref>\n\n====April 19====\n\n* Indiana: The states number of coronavirus cases increases to 11,210 and the death toll increases to 562.<ref>https://worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 31,424 with a death toll of 2,391.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dado |first1=Natasha |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 31,424; Death toll now at 2,391 with 3,237 recoveries reported |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/19/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-31424-death-toll-now-at-2391-with-3237-recoveries-reported/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 20====\n\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 32,000 with a death toll of 2,468.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 32,000; Death toll now at 2,468 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/20/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-32000-death-toll-now-at-2468/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 21====\n\n* Indiana: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state reaches 12,097 with the death toll increasing to 630.<ref>https://worldometers.info/coronavirus/country/us/</ref>\n* Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 32,967 with a death toll of 2,700.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 32,967; Death toll now at 2,700 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/21/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-32967-death-toll-now-at-2700/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=22 April 2020}}</ref>\n* Georgia: Governor Kemp announced on April 20 that many businesses could reopen on April 24, including \"gyms, hair salons, bowling alleys and tattoo parlors\", with restaurants and movie theaters allowed to reopen on April 27.<ref>https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-georgia-brian-kemp-governor-businesses-reopen-friday/</ref> This move has brought widespread condemnation from inside and outside Georgia,<ref><https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-georgia-brian-kemp-governor-businesses-reopen-friday/></ref><ref><https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/2020/04/21/georgia-leads-race-become-americas-no-1-death-destination/></ref> with Atlanta Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms saying she will \"continue to ask Atlantans to please stay at home\" and Stacy Abrams, the 2018 Democratic candidate for governor, calling reopening \"dangerously incompetent.<ref><https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-georgia-brian-kemp-governor-businesses-reopen-friday/></ref> The Institute for Health Metrics and Evaluation's April 21 prediction lists the earliest safe date for Georgia to shift from social distancing measures as June 19.<ref><http://www.healthdata.org/covid/updates></ref> As of April 21, the state had over 20,000 confirmed cases.<ref><https://www.ajc.com/news/breaking-news/breaking-nearly-800-coronavirus-deaths-881-confirmed-cases-georgia/P8bqjdUNaCtO39N7lQpWmN/></ref>\n\n====April 22====\n*Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 33,966 with a death toll of 2,813.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 35,291; Death toll now at 2,977 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/23/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-35291-death-toll-now-at-2977/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====April 23====\n*Michigan: The total number of cases of coronavirus in the state increases to 35,291 with a death toll of 2,977.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hutchinson |first1=Derick |title=Michigan coronavirus (COVID-19) cases up to 35,291; Death toll now at 2,977 |url=https://www.clickondetroit.com/health/2020/04/23/michigan-coronavirus-covid-19-cases-up-to-35291-death-toll-now-at-2977/ |website=clickondetroit.com |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{notelist}}\n\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{Portal bar|United States|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n[[Category:Timeline of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|United States]]\n[[Category:United States history timelines|Coronavirus]]\n\n[[de:COVID-19-Pandemie in den Vereinigten Staaten#Verlauf]]\n[[fr:Pand\u00e9mie de maladie \u00e0 coronavirus de 2020 aux \u00c9tats-Unis#Chronologie et statistiques]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Timeline of ongoing pandemic in the United States}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\nThe following is a timeline of the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bact.nizesystems.com/|title=Bay Area COVID-19 Tracker (BACT) {{!}} Nize Systems|website=bact.nizesystems.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States medical cases chart}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States cases by state}}\n\n==Timeline==\n===January===\n\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in California#January|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)#January}}\n\n====Prior to January 19====\n \nOn December 31, 2019 the [[U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) became aware of cases in China and began developing reports for the [[Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) on January 1.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national-security/2020/04/04/coronavirus-government-dysfunction/?arc404=true|title=The U.S. was beset by denial and dysfunction as the coronavirus raged|date=April 4, 2020|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_Response1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/us/politics/coronavirus-trump-response.html?|title=He Could Have Seen What Was Coming: Behind Trump's Failure on the Virus|date=April 11, 2020|via=nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 2, China disciplines eight doctors for \"rumor-mongering\" after they warned others on social media about the outbreak. This discouraged others from reporting about the coronavirus, which was not publicly disclosed by China until January 20.<ref name=\"AP_China_Delay\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/68a9e1b91de4ffc166acd6012d82c2f9|title=China didn't warn public of likely pandemic for 6 key days|date=April 15, 2020|via=apnews.com}}</ref> Dr. Li Wenliang, who later died of the virus, was one of them. Chinese officials later exonerated him and apologized to his family in March.<ref name=\"AP_Exonerate1\">{{cite news|url=https://apnews.com/6f2e666485e9abae4bb112251eca77be|title=China exonerates doctor rreprimanded for warning of virus|date=March 19, 2020|via=apnews.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 3, the CDC Director Robert Redfield was notified by a counterpart in China that a \"mysterious respiratory illness was spreading in Wuhan [China]\". Redfield notified HHS Secretary [[Alex Azar]] shortly thereafter, who shared his report with the [[National Security Council]] (NSC). According to ''The Washington Post'', warnings about the virus were included in the [[President's Daily Brief]] in early January, an indicator of the emphasis placed on the virus by the intelligence community.<ref name=\"NYT_Response1\"/><ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\nOn January 5, the WHO reported a \"pneumonia of unknown cause\" in Wuhan, China. The WHO advised against travel or trade restrictions at the time.<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/04/15/835011346/a-timeline-of-coronavirus-comments-from-president-trump-and-who|title=A Timeline Of Coronavirus Comments From President Trump And WHO|date=April 15, 2020|via=npr.org}}</ref>\n\nOn January 6, CDC Director offered in a letter to Chinese officials to send a team of CDC scientists to assist China. However, China did not accept the offer for several weeks, which delayed the U.S. access to the virus, important for developing diagnostic tests and a vaccine.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/> However, China did release genetic data on the new coronavirus on January 9.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.statnews.com/2020/01/09/chinese-scientists-obtain-genetic-sequence-of-mysterious-virus-a-key-step-in-containment-efforts/|title=Chinese scientists obtain genetic sequence of mysterious virus, a key step in containment efforts|date=January 9, 2020|via=statnews.com}}</ref>\n\nDuring the week of January 6, HHS officials convened an intra-agency task force including Redfield (CDC), Azar (HHS), and [[Anthony S. Fauci]], Director of the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]].<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\nOn January 8, the CDC issued its first public alert about the coronavirus.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\nOn January 9, the WHO issued a statement naming the disease as a new coronavirus in Wuhan.<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nOn January 14, the WHO tweeted that \"...{{nbsp}}investigations conducted by the Chinese authorities have found no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission of the novel #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)\".<ref name=\"WHO tweet\">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/WHO/status/1217043229427761152|title=WHO No Human-to-Human Transmission Tweet |date=January 14, 2020| |website=twitter.com}}</ref> The head of China's National Health Commission, Ma Xiaowei, confidentially provided \"grim\" situation assessment to key Chinese health officials. The related memo stated that \"human-to-human transmission is possible.\" An investigation by ''AP News'' indicated that the reporting of a case in Thailand prompted the meeting, as well as the risk of spread with heightened travel during the Chinese New Year and various political considerations. However, the Chinese public is not warned until January 20.<ref name=\"AP_China_Delay\"/>\n\nBeginning January 17, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] dispatched public health experts to screen incoming airport passengers at John F. Kennedy International Airport in New York, San Francisco, and Los Angeles, adding monitors at Chicago and Atlanta in late January.<ref>Santhanam, Laura. (24 January 2020). \"CDC confirms 2nd U.S. case of novel coronavirus in Chicago\". [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/health/cdc-confirms-second-u-s-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-chicago PBS website] Retrieved 2 April 2020.</ref>\n\nOn January 18, HHS Secretary Azar discussed the coronavirus outbreak with President Trump, who criticized Azar for being \"alarmist\".<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\n====January 20\u201328====\n\nOn January 20, both the WHO and Chinese authorities announced the confirmation that human-to-human transmission of the coronavirus had already occurred.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Kessler |first1=Glenn |title=Trump's false claim that the WHO said the coronavirus was 'not communicable' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/17/trumps-false-claim-that-who-said-coronavirus-was-not-communicable/ |accessdate=April 17, 2020 |work=The Washington Post |date=April 17, 2020 |archiveurl=http://archive.is/7Pgq4 |archivedate=April 17, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kuo |first1=Lily |title=China confirms human-to-human transmission of coronavirus |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/20/coronavirus-spreads-to-beijing-as-china-confirms-new-cases |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe first U.S. case of the new virus was also reported on January 20, in an American citizen traveling from Wuhan, China, to his home in Washington state.<ref name=nejm>[https://www.nejm.org/doi/10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 \"First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States\"], ''The New England Journal of Medicine'', March 5, 2020</ref>\n\nBy January 20, the CDC developed its own coronavirus test, and used it to evaluate the first U.S. case. Testing is essential to conducting [[Public health surveillance|community surveillance]] and [[contact tracing]] to measure the spread of the virus and establish local quarantines, preventing further spread. As it typically does, the CDC developed its own test. The CDC test used three genetic sequences or \"probes\", rather than using a German-developed, two-sequence test that the WHO was distributing. However, the CDC test is soon found to be defective, with the third probe giving inconclusive results. The CDC directed state health department labs to send all samples to the CDC lab in Atlanta for evaluation (significantly increasing time to confirm diagnosis). By mid-February, the U.S. is still testing only about a hundred samples per day, versus thousands per day in other countries. With limited testing capacity, the scope of testing remained extremely narrow. This contributed to the inability to establish effective surveillance and contact tracing programs essential to containing the spread of the virus. Researchers concluded in late February that \"the virus had probably been [[Transmission (medicine)|spreading]] for weeks\" person-to-person. Sometime after February 24, the CDC directs states to use a workaround, using just two of the three probes and evaluate them locally.<ref name=\"NYT_Test1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/28/us/testing-coronavirus-pandemic.html|title=The Lost Month:How a Failure to Test Blinded the U.S. to Covid-19|date=March 28, 2020|via=nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 20, [[Communist Party of China|Chinese Communist Party]] [[General Secretary of the Communist Party of China|general secretary]] [[Xi Jinping]] and [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] [[Premier of the People's Republic of China|premier]] [[Li Keqiang]] issue the first public warning about the coronavirus to Chinese citizens. An investigation by ''AP News'' alleged that from January 14 to January 20, Chinese authorities took additional confidential action to mobilize their pandemic response but did not alert the public. Alerting the public six days sooner might have avoided \"the collapse of the Wuhan medical system\" according to one epidemiologist.<ref name=\"AP_China_Delay\"/>\n\n[[File:Donald Trump Coronavirus briefing.jpg|thumb|President [[Donald Trump]] received a briefing on the coronavirus on January 29, 2020.|alt=]]\n\nThe first reported case in the U.S. was in [[Washington (state)|Washington state]] on January 21, 2020, which affected a man who had returned from [[Wuhan]], China. He was released after two weeks of treatment. A few days later, another case was reported in Chicago, by a woman who had also just returned from Wuhan.<ref>[https://wgntv.com/news/chicago-woman-infects-husband-with-coronavirus-first-human-to-human-spread-in-us/ \"Chicago woman infects husband with coronavirus, US issues travel warning\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130121/https://wgntv.com/news/chicago-woman-infects-husband-with-coronavirus-first-human-to-human-spread-in-us/ |date=March 12, 2020 }}, WGN9 TV, Chicago, IL. January 30, 2020</ref> A third case was confirmed a day later in [[Orange County, California|Orange County]], California.<ref>[https://www.ocregister.com/2020/02/04/risk-of-catching-coronavirus-in-so-cal-is-low-health-officials-say/ \"Orange County coronavirus patient released, in good condition, health officials say\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205195530/https://www.ocregister.com/2020/02/04/risk-of-catching-coronavirus-in-so-cal-is-low-health-officials-say/ |date=February 5, 2020 }}, ''Orange County Register'', February 4, 2020</ref> \n\nOn January 22, Trump received his first public question from a reporter regarding whether he was concerned about the coronavirus. Trump responded: \"No, not at all. And we have it totally under control. It's one person coming in from China{{nbsp}}... It's going to be just fine.\"<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\nOn January 23, Chinese authorities shut down Wuhan, a city of 11 million, which heightened the urgency for the U.S. response team. ''The Washington Post'' reported that Secretary Azar (HHS) instructed his team to establish a surveillance mechanism shortly thereafter, but the money and diagnostic tests \"would elude U.S. officials for months\". The entire Hubei province, which contains Wuhan, was locked-down January 30.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/> \n\nOn January 23, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) publishes a statement on the coronavirus, indicating that: \"Human-to-human transmission is occurring and a preliminary [[Basic reproduction number|R0 estimate]] of 1.4-2.5 was presented. Amplification has occurred in one health care facility. Of confirmed cases, 25% are reported to be severe. The source is still unknown (most likely an animal reservoir) and the extent of human-to-human transmission is still not clear.\" At the time, the fatality rate was 4% (17 of 557). The WHO recommended that: \"[A]ll countries should be prepared for containment, including active surveillance, early detection, isolation and case management, contact tracing and prevention of onward spread of 2019-nCoV infection, and to share full data with WHO.\"<ref name=\"WHO_Jan23\">{{cite news|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/23-01-2020-statement-on-the-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=Statement on the meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|date=January 23, 2020|via=who.int}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, the U.S. Senate was briefed on the coronavirus by key health officials. U.S. Senators [[Richard M. Burr]], [[Kelly Loeffler]], [[Dianne Feinstein]], and [[James Inhofe]] allegedly sold stock thereafter, prior to significant declines in the stock market. In Senator Loeffler's case, the sales began the same day as the briefing. All denied any wrongdoing, citing various reasons. Senator Burr faced calls for his resignation.<ref name=\"NYT_Senators_Sell1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/20/us/politics/kelly-loeffler-richard-burr-insider-trading.html|title=Kelly Loeffler and Richard Burr Were Briefed on Coronavirus. Then They Sold Stocks. What Now?|date=March 20, 2020|via=nytimes.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 24, President Trump praised China for its coronavirus efforts in a tweet.<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nTwo more cases were confirmed on January 26, similarly by two people who had returned from Wuhan.<ref>[https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2020/01/26/public-health-officials-confirm-first-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-la-county/ \"Public Health Officials Confirm First Case Of Novel Coronavirus In LA County\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200126192042/https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2020/01/26/public-health-officials-confirm-first-case-of-novel-coronavirus-in-la-county/ |date=January 26, 2020 }}, KCAL TV, January 26, 2020</ref> All cases to this point were allowed to self-isolate at home for two weeks, whereafter they were assumed to be no longer infected or contagious.\n\nOn January 27, the WHO assessed the risk of the coronavirus to be \"high at the global level\".<ref>{{cite news |title=WHO says global risk of China virus is 'high' |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/world/2020/01/27/who-says-global-risk-of-china-virus-is-039high039 |accessdate=April 19, 2020 |agency=[[Agence France Presse]] |date=January 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====January 29\u201331====\n\nOn January 29, the U.S. formally announced a Coronavirus Task Force, including senior officials such as acting White House Chief of Staff [[Mick Mulvaney]] and others at HHS, CDC, and the State Department. President Trump attended the meeting on January 29, and tweeted related photos.<ref>[https://twitter.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1222672488934584324 Twitter-Donald Trump-Briefing on Coronavirus-January 29, 2020]</ref> However, the scope was limited initially to the logistics of keeping travelers out of the U.S. from China, and evacuating U.S. citizens. They did not initially focus on testing or supplies in the U.S.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/> \n\nOn January 29, the U.S. government evacuated 195 State Department employees from Wuhan along with their families and other U.S. citizens to [[March Air Reserve Base]] near [[Riverside, California]], where they are kept under quarantine for 14 days, although none had been infected.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-usa/two-planes-left-wuhan-china-en-route-to-us-state-department-idUSKBN20105M \"Two more U.S. evacuation planes leave coronavirus epicenter Wuhan\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216045906/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-usa/two-planes-left-wuhan-china-en-route-to-us-state-department-idUSKBN20105M |date=February 16, 2020 }}, Reuters, February 6, 2020</ref><ref>[https://timesofsandiego.com/tech/2020/02/10/with-no-signs-of-infection-coronavirus-evacuees-in-riverside-set-to-end-quarantine/ With No Signs of Infection, Coronavirus Evacuees in Riverside Set to End Quarantine]{{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312130817/https://timesofsandiego.com/tech/2020/02/10/with-no-signs-of-infection-coronavirus-evacuees-in-riverside-set-to-end-quarantine/ |date=March 12, 2020 }}, Times of San Diego, February 10, 2020</ref> \n\n''The New York Times'' reported that President Trump was told \"at the time\" of a January 29 memo by trade adviser [[Peter Navarro]] that the coronavirus could cause as many as 500,000 deaths and trillions in economic damage. Further, on January 30, Department of Health and Human Services Secretary [[Alex M. Azar II]] warned President Trump about the \"possibility of a pandemic\".<ref name=\"NYT_Response1\"/>\n\nOn January 29, WHO Health Emergency program leader Dr. Mike Ryan states in a press briefing: \"The whole world needs to be on alert now{{nbsp}}... and be ready for any cases that come from the epicenter{{nbsp}}...\" At the time, 68 cases had been confirmed outside China, affecting persons in 15 countries.<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nOn January 30, the first case of person-to-person transmission is confirmed in Chicago, between a married couple, after the wife returned from China.<ref name=\"Marketwatch\">[https://www.marketwatch.com/story/coronavirus-update-a-new-task-force-195-us-citizens-in-isolation-and-who-to-decide-if-its-a-public-health-emergency-2020-01-30 \"First U.S. case of person-to-person transmission confirmed, 195 U.S. citizens in isolation and WHO declares a public health emergency\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130221503/https://www.marketwatch.com/story/coronavirus-update-a-new-task-force-195-us-citizens-in-isolation-and-who-to-decide-if-its-a-public-health-emergency-2020-01-30 |date=January 30, 2020 }}, ''MarketWatch'', January 30, 2010</ref> \n\nOn January 30, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) named the coronavirus outbreak that originated in Wuhan, China, a [[Public Health Emergency of International Concern]], warning that \"all countries should be prepared for containment, including active surveillance, early detection, isolation and case management, contact tracing and prevention of onward spread\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Boseley |first1=Sarah |title=WHO declares coronavirus a global health emergency |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/jan/30/who-declares-coronavirus-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kennedy |first1=Merrit |title=WHO Declares Coronavirus Outbreak A Global Health Emergency |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/goatsandsoda/2020/01/30/798894428/who-declares-coronavirus-outbreak-a-global-health-emergency |accessdate=19 April 2020 |work=[[NPR]] |date=30 January 2020}}</ref> The statement also praised the \"impressive\" Chinese response.<ref name=\"WHO_PHE\">{{cite news|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-statement-on-ihr-emergency-committee-on-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)|title=WHO Director-General's statement on IHR Emergency Committee on Novel Coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|date=January 30, 2020|via=who.int}}</ref> The WHO also released a statement that included: \"The Committee believes that it is still possible to interrupt virus spread, provided that countries put in place strong measures to detect disease early, isolate and treat cases, trace contacts, and promote social distancing measures commensurate with the risk.\"<ref name=\"WHO_2ndmtg\">{{cite news|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/30-01-2020-statement-on-the-second-meeting-of-the-international-health-regulations-(2005)-emergency-committee-regarding-the-outbreak-of-novel-coronavirus-(2019-ncov)?|title=Statement on the second meeting of the International Health Regulations (2005) Emergency Committee regarding the outbreak of novel coronavirus (2019-nCoV)|date=January 30, 2020|via=who.int}}</ref> However, the federal government and U.S. states did not direct their populations to social distance (e.g., stay at home except for essential travel) until March 19 (California), Illinois (March 20) and others around that time.<ref name=\"NPR_IL\">{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/coronavirus-live-updates/2020/03/20/819295135/illinois-gov-issues-stay-at-home-order-to-fight-coronavirus|title=Illinois Gov. Issues Stay-At-Home Order To Fight Coronavirus|date=March 20, 2020|via=npr.org}}</ref> Further, as late as April 8, five states had no social distancing rules and three others had rules for only parts of the state.<ref name=\"Vox_SD1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/4/10/21216216/coronavirus-social-distancing-texas-unacast-climate-change|title=The US has a collective action problem that's larger than the coronavirus crisis|date=April 10, 2020|via=vox.com}}</ref>\n\nOn January 31, another case of a person who returned from Wuhan is confirmed in California, which marks the seventh known case in the U.S.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/31/california-and-cdc-officials-confirm-7th-case-of-coronavirus-in-the-us.html \"CDC officials confirm 7th US case of coronavirus, in California man who traveled to China\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201021201/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/01/31/california-and-cdc-officials-confirm-7th-case-of-coronavirus-in-the-us.html |date=February 1, 2020 }}, CNBC, January 31, 2020</ref> \n\nOn January 31, the Trump Administration, through the U.S. [[Department of Health and Human Services]], declared a public health emergency, and imposed a mandatory 14-day [[quarantine]] for any U.S. citizens who has visited Hubei Province in China within the preceding two weeks. It also began denying entry of non-U.S. nationals who had traveled to China within the preceding two weeks. This was the first such travel restriction by the U.S. in more than 50 years.<ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-reports-first-coronavirus-cases-as-china-allies-limit-ties-11580467046 \"U.S. Imposes Entry Restrictions Over Coronavirus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200201022426/https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-k-reports-first-coronavirus-cases-as-china-allies-limit-ties-11580467046 |date=February 1, 2020 }}, ''Wall Street Journal'', January 31, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/01/world/asia/china-coronavirus-us-australia.html \"China Increasingly Walled Off as Countries Seek to Stem Coronavirus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200204225148/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/01/world/asia/china-coronavirus-us-australia.html |date=February 4, 2020 }}, ''New York Times'', February 1, 2020</ref> \n\nPresident Trump repeatedly claimed credit for acting early with the travel ban. However, ''The Washington Post'' reported that 300,000 people traveled to the U.S. from China during the month prior to the ban.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/> ''The New York Times'' reported that more than 40,000 persons traveled from China to the U.S. after the January 31 partial ban, and around 430,000 total between the December 31, 2019 disclosure of the outbreak by China and April 4.<ref name=\"NYT_China_Travel1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/04/us/coronavirus-china-travel-restrictions.html|title=430,000 People Have Traveled From China to U.S. Since Coronavirus Surfaced|date=April 4, 2020|via=nytimes.com}}</ref> ''The Washington Post'' reported that six other countries had restricted travel from China before January 30, six did so on January 31, and by the time U.S. travel restrictions became effective on February 2, 38 other countries had taken action before or at the same time as the U.S. restrictions. The earliest action was Singapore on January 23.<ref name=\"WaPo_Restrictions1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2020/04/07/trumps-claim-that-he-imposed-first-china-ban/|title=Trump's claim that he imposed the first 'China ban'|date=April 7, 2020|via=washingtonpost.com}}</ref> Flights from Europe were not banned until March 11, with hundreds of thousands crossing the Atlantic into the U.S., due to disputes about the impact on the U.S. economy among Trump Administration officials.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\n===February===\n\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in California#February|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts#February|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)#February}}\n[[File:Senior DOD Official Holds News Conference feb 3 2020 DOD 107640372-1280x720-2765k-5e6fb7fa80e93.webm|thumb|start=01:37|A senior DOD official holds a news conference at [[the Pentagon]] on February{{nbsp}}3]]\n[[File:White House Press Briefing (49591617778).jpg|thumb|Members of the Coronavirus Task Force hold a press briefing at the White House on February 26]]\n\n====February 1\u201315====\n\nNew cases are being reported throughout the country nearly every day. Many are people who have recently returned from China, including a college student from Boston and a woman in California who returned from Wuhan.<ref name=\"uk.reuters.com\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-health-usa-california-idUKKBN1ZX01P|title=Ninth case of fast-moving coronavirus confirmed in U.S.|date=February 2, 2020|work=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200203011127/https://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-health-usa-california-idUKKBN1ZX01P|archive-date=February 3, 2020|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> Two more cases of person-to-person transmission are reported in California.\n\n''The Washington Post'' reported that HHS Secretary Azar, responding to concerns about a \"startling [[Shortages related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|shortage]]\" of essential medical supplies (masks, gowns, gloves, etc.) wrote letters in late January and early February asking for additional funding. Since China also needed such supplies, replenishing them could be difficult as much of the manufacturing was in China. He also made a formal request for $4 billion on February 5, which \"OMB officials and others at the White House greeted as an outrage\". Congress later increased the figure to $8 billion, and Trump signed it into law on March 6, but this delay meant that the U.S. would increasingly compete with other nations for such supplies.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\n\nOn February 3, 49 members of Congress signed a letter to CDC Director Redfield highlighting the urgency of distributing a rapid diagnostic kit that could be processed locally, rather than centrally at the CDC in Atlanta, which they referred to as an \"unsustainable bottleneck\" as the number of suspected cases rise.<ref name=\"NYT_Test1\"/><ref>[https://kilmer.house.gov/imo/media/doc/Letter%20to%20CDC%20Director%20Redfield%202.3.2020.pdf Congress of the United States-Letter to Dr. Robert R. Redfield-February 3, 2020]</ref>\n\nOn February 3, ''Reuters'' reported that WHO chief Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesus stated that there was no need for measures that \"unnecessarily interfere with international travel and trade\" to halt the coronavirus. He praised the Chinese response, and referred to the virus's spread as \"minimal and slow\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-who/who-chief-says-widespread-travel-bans-not-needed-to-beat-china-virus-idUSKBN1ZX1H3|title=WHO chief says widespread travel bans not needed to beat China virus|date=February 3, 2020|via=reuters.com}}</ref>\n\nOn February 5, the twelfth case is discovered: another college student from Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-05-20-intl-hnk/index.html|title=Wisconsin coronavirus patient is isolated at home|last=Lin Erdman|first=Shelby|date=5 February 2020|website=CNN.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206030623/https://edition.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-02-05-20-intl-hnk/index.html|archive-date=February 6, 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> That day, the U.S. evacuates 345 citizens from Hubei Province and takes them to two air bases in California to be quarantined for 14 days.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/us/coronavirus-flights-wuhan.html \"Hundreds of Americans Were Evacuated From the Coronavirus Epicenter. Now Comes the Wait.\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206130218/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/05/us/coronavirus-flights-wuhan.html |date=February 6, 2020 }}, ''New York Times'', February 5, 2020</ref> Another government evacuation flight takes place on February 6, containing 300 passengers, most of who are taken to bases in Nebraska and Texas. By this time, more than 500 people are quarantined at three air bases.<ref>[https://q13fox.com/2020/02/06/planeloads-of-americans-flee-growing-coronavirus-outbreak-in-wuhan-as-12th-case-is-reported-in-the-us/ \"Planeloads of Americans flee growing coronavirus outbreak in Wuhan as 12th case is reported in the US\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200208142723/https://q13fox.com/2020/02/06/planeloads-of-americans-flee-growing-coronavirus-outbreak-in-wuhan-as-12th-case-is-reported-in-the-us/ |date=February 8, 2020 }}, ''Q13Fox'', February 6, 2020</ref> \n\nOn February 6, the [[Centers for Disease Control]] began sending 90 of its own viral detection tests to state-run labs which discovered the tests were inadequate and viral samples had to be shipped to the Atlanta CDC lab instead.<ref name=\"WaPo_Denial1\"/>\nAlso on February 6, the WHO Director-General stated that: \"We have shipped 250,000 tests to more than 70 laboratories around the world, and we're training lab workers to use them.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.who.int/dg/speeches/detail/who-director-general-s-opening-remarks-at-the-media-briefing-on-2019-novel-coronavirus|title=WHO Director-General's opening remarks at the media briefing on 2019 novel coronavirus|date=February 6, 2020|via=who.int}}</ref> Researchers at Stanford and other laboratories had developed tests following the WHO protocol, but \"relatively tight\" rules at the [[Food and Drug Administration]] discouraged them from using them. These rules were not relaxed until early March.<ref name=\"NYT_Response1\"/>\n\nLater studies found the first known US death due to coronavirus occurred on February 6th, in [[Santa Clara County]], California.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/health/article/First-known-U-S-coronavirus-death-occurred-on-15217316.php |title=First known U.S. coronavirus death occurred on Feb. 6 in Santa Clara County |access-date=22 April 2020|website=SF Chronicle |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 11, WHO Director-General Tedros Adhanom Ghebreyesu stated in a briefing: \"[A] virus is more powerful in creating political, economic and social upheaval than any terrorist attack{{nbsp}}... If the world doesn't want to wake up and consider this enemy virus and Public Enemy Number 1, I don't think we will learn our lessons.\"<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nFrom February 12 to 15, three more cases are confirmed, all who travelled from Wuhan, and are similarly quarantined.<ref>[https://www.kcra.com/article/2nd-case-new-coronavirus-confirmed-among-china-evacuees/30902073# \"2nd evacuee from China tests positive for coronavirus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200213014119/https://www.kcra.com/article/2nd-case-new-coronavirus-confirmed-among-china-evacuees/30902073 |date=February 13, 2020 }}, KCRA, February 12, 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.cbs8.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/1-of-2-patients-released-from-isolation-at-uc-san-diego-health-after-recovering-from-covid-19/509-e3bcfa0c-3c5b-4519-b210-e1f072ae353a \"1 of 2 patients released from isolation at UC San Diego Health after recovering from COVID-19\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222104915/https://www.cbs8.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/1-of-2-patients-released-from-isolation-at-uc-san-diego-health-after-recovering-from-covid-19/509-e3bcfa0c-3c5b-4519-b210-e1f072ae353a |date=February 22, 2020 }}, ''CBS8'', February 19, 2020</ref>\n\n====February 15\u201329====\n\nOn February 15, the government evacuates 338 U.S. nationals stranded aboard the cruise ship [[Diamond Princess (ship)|''Diamond Princess'']], which had been held in quarantine in [[Yokohama, Japan]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51514102 \"Coronavirus: US to evacuate citizens from Diamond Princess\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200216050642/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51514102 |date=February 16, 2020 }}, ''BBC'', February 15, 2020</ref> Fourteen of those repatriated people are infected with the virus.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-japan-cruiseship-usa/u-s-state-dept-says-fourteen-test-positive-for-coronavirus-from-cruise-ship-in-japan-idUSKBN20B0U9 \"U.S. flies 338 Americans home from cruise ship, including 14 with coronavirus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200217112803/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-japan-cruiseship-usa/u-s-state-dept-says-fourteen-test-positive-for-coronavirus-from-cruise-ship-in-japan-idUSKBN20B0U9 |date=February 17, 2020 }}, Reuters, February 17, 2020</ref> Five more nationals who were also reported as being infected are evacuated from the ship the following week, and are quarantined at an airbase in California. Six more cases are subsequently confirmed among those who were evacuated from the cruise ship.<ref>[https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/health/evacuated-passengers-test-positive-coronavirus/index.html \"13 Americans moved to Omaha facility from evacuation flights, US officials say\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200218210337/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/17/health/evacuated-passengers-test-positive-coronavirus/index.html |date=February 18, 2020 }}, CNN, February 18, 2020</ref>\n\n''The New York Times'' reported that the Chief Medical Officer of the [[Department of Homeland Security]], Dr. Duane C. Caneva, continued hosting a series of coronavirus e-mail chains begun in January among a group of infectious disease experts from academia and government. The group referred to these chains as the \"Red Dawn\" e-mails, (a [[Red Dawn|movie reference]]). On February 17, an e-mail from one participant indicated that the type of social gathering on the ''Diamond Princess'' cruise ship wasn't that different from a mall, school, or work environment. Another February 17 e-mail indicated that non-pharmaceutical interventions (\"NPI\") such as school and business closures would be difficult for local officials to direct without federal action to provide political cover. By the third week of February, the group had \"effectively concluded that the United States had already lost the fight to contain the virus, and that it needed to switch to mitigation\" such as NPI's. This was based on the \"realization that many people in the country were likely infected and capable of spreading the disease, but not showing any symptoms.\" For instance, by the time of the European travel ban on March 11 (a containment strategy), the group considered such containment steps ineffective. Trump still had not directed NPI's as of March 11. As late as March 13, the CDC was still questioning the benefit of closing schools. Governors began to implement NPI's thereafter, \"largely without federal leadership\".<ref name=\"NYT_Red_Dawn1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/11/us/politics/coronavirus-red-dawn-emails-trump.html?|title=The 'Red Dawn' Emails: 8 Key Exchanges on the Faltering Response to the Coronavirus|date=April 11, 2020|work=nytimes.com|access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn February 20 and 21, two more cases of people who had returned from China are confirmed in California.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-21/coronavirus-humboldt-sacramento-county-total-california-cases-to-15 \"California's coronavirus cases now at 15, with new diagnoses in Humboldt, Sacramento areas\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200222020122/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-02-21/coronavirus-humboldt-sacramento-county-total-california-cases-to-15 |date=February 22, 2020 }}, ''Los Angeles Times'', February 21, 2020</ref> The first case of [[community transmission]], because it had no known origin, is confirmed in Solano County, California, on February 26.<ref>[https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/OPA/Pages/NR20-006.aspx \"CDC Confirms Possible First Instance of COVID-19 Community Transmission in California\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228203724/https://www.cdph.ca.gov/Programs/OPA/Pages/NR20-006.aspx |date=February 28, 2020 }}, ''Calif. Dept. of Public Health'', February 26, 2020</ref> A second case of unknown origin is confirmed two days later, also in California, followed by others in Oregon and Washington state.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/28/health/coronavirus-us-updates-california-patient/index.html \"New coronavirus cases in California and Oregon are second and third of unknown origin in US\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229001102/https://www.cnn.com/2020/02/28/health/coronavirus-us-updates-california-patient/index.html |date=February 29, 2020 }}, CNN, February 28, 2020</ref>\n\nOn February 24, President Trump tweets: \"The Coronavirus is very much under control in the USA{{nbsp}}... CDC and World Health [Organization] have been working hard and very smart.\"<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nOn February 25, HHS Secretary Azar testified before the U.S. Senate. ''[[National Geographic]]'' summarized his testimony, reporting that \"the [[Strategic National Stockpile]] has just 30 million [[surgical mask|surgical masks]] and 12 million [N95] [[respirator|respirators]] in reserve.\" An additional 300 million of each could be required to protect health workers. HHS said it intended to purchase as many as half a billion respirators and surgical face masks over the next year and a half. A previous 2015 CDC study found that seven billion N95 respirators might be necessary to handle a \"severe respiratory outbreak\". ''National Geographic'' concluded that the \"U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Akpan |first1=Nsikan |title=U.S. has only a fraction of the medical supplies it needs to combat coronavirus.|url=https://www.nationalgeographic.com/science/2020/03/us-america-has-fraction-medical-supplies-it-needs-to-combat-coronavirus/? |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[National Geographic (magazine)|National Geographic]] |date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn February 25, [[Nancy Messonnier|Dr. Nancy Messonnier]], Director of the CDC's [[National Center for Immunization and Respiratory Diseases]], delivered a briefing indicating that \"disruption to everyday life might be severe.\" ''The New York Times'' reported that President Trump was \"furious\", and HHS Secretary Azar attempted downplay her comments in a news conference later that day.<ref name=\"NYT_Response1\"/>\n\nOn February 26 at a news conference, President Trump said: \"When you have 15 people, and the 15 within a couple of days is going to be down close to zero, that's a pretty good job we've done.\"<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nOn February 26, Vice-President [[Michael Pence]] was appointed to lead the Coronavirus Task Force, replacing HHS Secretary Azar as the group's leader. Pence was the first official from within Trump's White House to coordinate the planning and response, two months after the government became aware of the coronavirus.<ref name=\"NYT_Response1\"/>\n\nOn February 29, the first death from coronavirus in the U.S. is reported at EvergreenHealth Medical Center in [[Kirkland, Washington]], followed by two other confirmed cases, those in a nursing home in the same city.<ref>[https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/1st-coronavirus-death-u-s-officials-say-n1145931 \"Washington state man becomes first U.S. death from coronavirus\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229192416/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/1st-coronavirus-death-u-s-officials-say-n1145931 |date=February 29, 2020 }}, NBC News, February 29, 2020</ref> New cases continue to show up in California and Illinois.<ref>[https://www.rollcall.com/2020/02/29/coronavirus-response-efforts-ramp-up-as-first-u-s-death-confirmed/ \"Coronavirus response efforts ramp up as first US death confirmed\"], ''Roll Call'', February 29, 2020</ref>\n\n===March===\n\n{{See also|2020 coronavirus pandemic in California#March|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Massachusetts#March|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Minnesota#March|2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington (state)#March|2020 coronavirus pandemic in Illinois}}\n\n====March 1\u20132====\n\n[[File:Coronavirus Task Force Meeting (49615398926).jpg|thumb|Vice President [[Mike Pence]] with White House coronavirus task force principals on March{{nbsp}}2 in the [[White House Situation Room]]]]\nIn New York, Governor [[Andrew Cuomo]] announces the state's first reported case of COVID-19: a woman in her late 30s, who apparently contracted the virus while traveling in Iran and is self-isolating at home, in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mobile.twitter.com/BNODesk/status/1234280201825193986 |title=Twitter |publisher=Twitter}}</ref> Oregon confirmed its second case, a household contact of its first case.<ref name=\"oregon.2.1\">{{cite web |url=https://content.govdelivery.com/accounts/ORDHS/bulletins/27ea91b |title=Second Positive Case of COVID-19 Appears in Oregon |website=The Oregon Health Authority and Department of Human Services |access-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref> The [[Rhode Island Department of Health]] announces a presumptive case in a person in their 40s who had traveled to Italy in mid-February,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ri.gov/press/view/37818 |title=First Presumptive Positive Case of COVID-19 Identified at RIDOH's State Health Laboratories |date=March 1, 2020 |website=RI.gov |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301172041/https://www.ri.gov/press/view/37818 |archive-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> and a second case, a teenager who had traveled with the first person.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/01/first-virus-case-confirmed-in-rhode-island/ |title=2 cases of COVID-19 virus confirmed in Rhode Island |date=March 1, 2020 |website=Press Herald |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302014934/https://www.pressherald.com/2020/03/01/first-virus-case-confirmed-in-rhode-island/ |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nOn March 2, coronavirus cases in the U.S. reach 100, including repatriated citizens from Wuhan or the ''Diamond Princess''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-02-20-intl-hnk/h_ab394740b4249012dc266df09451872f |title=There are now 100 cases of coronavirus in the US |date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302221314/https://www.cnn.com/asia/live-news/coronavirus-outbreak-03-02-20-intl-hnk/h_ab394740b4249012dc266df09451872f |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |publisher=CNN}}</ref> [[New Hampshire]] officials announce the state's first case, an employee with [[Dartmouth\u2013Hitchcock Medical Center]] who had been to Italy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/1st-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-in-nh/2084452/ |title=1st Confirmed Case of Coronavirus in NH |website=NBC Boston |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303123944/https://www.nbcboston.com/news/local/1st-confirmed-case-of-coronavirus-in-nh/2084452/ |archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 3\u20134====\n\nOn March 3, when the state has no confirmed cases, Ohio Governor [[Mike DeWine]] cancels the [[Arnold Sports Festival|Arnold Classic]] due to coronavirus concerns, a move which the ''Washington Post'' said seemed radical at the time.<ref name=\":8:\">{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-ohio-dewine-outbreak/2020/03/16/9bde6b1e-67b2-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html |title=Ohio Gov. Mike DeWine's coronavirus response has become a national guide to the crisis |last=Witte |first=Griff |last2=Zezima |first2=Katie |date=16 March 2020 |website=[[Washington Post]] |url-status=live |access-date=17 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317142655/https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-ohio-dewine-outbreak/2020/03/16/9bde6b1e-67b2-11ea-9923-57073adce27c_story.html |archive-date=March 17, 2020 }}</ref> On March 3, [[Arizona]]'s Department of Health Services reports a new confirmed case in Maricopa County, a man in his 20s who had made contact with a case outside of Arizona. The man is isolated in his home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.abc15.com/news/region-phoenix-metro/central-phoenix/coronavirus-in-arizona-officials-confirm-new-presumptive-positive-case |title=Coronavirus in Arizona: Officials confirm new 'presumptive positive' case in Maricopa County |date=March 3, 2020 |publisher=[[KNXV-TV|ABC 15 Arizona]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304001348/https://www.abc15.com/news/region-phoenix-metro/central-phoenix/coronavirus-in-arizona-officials-confirm-new-presumptive-positive-case |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> In New Hampshire, public health officials confirm a second case of coronavirus in an individual who made contact with the first case after the first case defied quarantine orders and attended a private event organized by [[Dartmouth College]]'s [[Tuck School of Business]] in [[White River Junction, Vermont]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.unionleader.com/news/health/coronavirus/second-case-of-coronavirus-in-nh-tests-positive/article_2da63bb4-818e-5774-a213-f40777cb0180.html |title=Second case of coronavirus in NH tests positive |last=Feely |first=Paul |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[New Hampshire Union Leader]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304052458/https://www.unionleader.com/news/health/coronavirus/second-case-of-coronavirus-in-nh-tests-positive/article_2da63bb4-818e-5774-a213-f40777cb0180.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/nh-coronavirus-patient-breaks-isolation-potentially-exposing-others-n1148641 |title=N.H. coronavirus patient breaks isolation, potentially exposing others |last=Edwards |first=Erika |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[NBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304004726/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/nh-coronavirus-patient-breaks-isolation-potentially-exposing-others-n1148641 |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> New York officials announce the state's second confirmed case: a man in his 50s in [[New Rochelle]], [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lohud.com/story/news/politics/politics-on-the-hudson/2020/03/03/coronavirus-new-york-westchester-man-has-states-second-confirmed-case/4937479002/ |title=Coronavirus in New York: Westchester man has state's second confirmed case |last=Campbell |first=Jon |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[The Journal News]], White Plains, NY |url-status=live |access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-03/nyc-school-closed-as-a-precaution-on-suspected-virus-case |title=New York Man Hospitalized With Coronavirus; Origin Unknown |last=Clukey |first=Keshia |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |url-status=live |access-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref> who had not recently traveled to any foreign countries affected by the outbreak.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/03/bronx-jewish-day-school-closes-for-suspected-coronavirus-case/ |title=New York confirms second coronavirus case as Jewish schools close over virus fears |last=Algar |first=Selim |last2=Hogan |first2=Bernadette |date=March 3, 2020 |website=[[The New York Post]] |url-status=live |access-date=March 3, 2020 |last3=Steinbuch |first3=Yaron}}</ref> In [[North Carolina]], Governor [[Roy Cooper]] announces the state's first confirmed case: a person who had traveled to Washington and was \"exposed at a long term care facility\". They are in stable condition and in isolation at their home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/live-first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-north-carolina-health-officials-say/ar-BB10Hs7e |title=First case of coronavirus confirmed in North Carolina, health officials say |publisher=MSN |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303210148/https://www.msn.com/en-us/health/medical/live-first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-north-carolina-health-officials-say/ar-BB10Hs7e |archive-date=March 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, the US [[Department of Homeland Security]] confirms that a \"contract medical screener\" for the CDC working at the [[Los Angeles International Airport]] tested positive for coronavirus. The individual is in self-isolation at home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/medical-screener-lax-airport-tests-positive-coronavirus-n1149986 |title=Medical screener at LAX airport tests positive for coronavirus |last=Strickler |first=Laura |last2=Blankstein |first2=Andrew |date=March 4, 2020 |website=[[NBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305014721/https://www.nbcnews.com/health/health-news/medical-screener-lax-airport-tests-positive-coronavirus-n1149986 |archive-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> New York officials confirm four new cases of coronavirus: the wife, son, and daughter of the second case, as well as the man's neighbor who drove him to the hospital. The new cases prompt the partial closure of the main campus of [[Yeshiva University]], where the man's son is a student, as well as the high school in the [[Bronx]] borough of New York City where the daughter is a student.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://newyork.cbslocal.com/2020/03/04/coronavirus-update-new-rochelle-man-self-quarantine/ |title=Coronavirus Update: 6 Cases Confirmed In N.Y. As Family, Neighbor Of Infected New Rochelle Man Test Positive For Virus |date=March 4, 2020 |publisher=[[WLNY]] |access-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/04/yeshiva-university-in-new-york-city-cancels-class-after-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html |title=New York family of four all test positive for coronavirus as state cases climb |last=Feuer |first=William |date=March 4, 2020 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304210751/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/04/yeshiva-university-in-new-york-city-cancels-class-after-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Gold |first=Michael |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-yeshiva-university.html |title=Coronavirus in N.Y.: Family of Westchester Man and Neighbor Confirmed |date=March 4, 2020 |work=[[The New York Times]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304212724/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/04/nyregion/coronavirus-nyc-yeshiva-university.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, another five confirmed cases are reported in a friend of the second case, as well as that friend's wife, two sons, and daughter.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/04/ny-gov-cuomo-confirms-5-new-cases-of-coronavirus-bringing-the-state-total-to-11.html |title=NY Gov. Cuomo confirms 5 new cases of coronavirus: 'This is literally like trying to stop air' |date=March 4, 2020 |publisher=[[WLNY]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304234936/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/04/ny-gov-cuomo-confirms-5-new-cases-of-coronavirus-bringing-the-state-total-to-11.html |archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/04/five-more-new-york-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-bringing-state-total-to-11/ |title=Five more New York coronavirus cases confirmed, bringing state total to 11 |last=Hogan |first=Bernadette |last2=Feis |first2=Aaron |date=March 4, 2020 |website=[[The New York Post]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308050724/https://nypost.com/2020/03/04/five-more-new-york-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-bringing-state-total-to-11/ |archive-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> \n\nHHS announced the intent to purchase approximately 500 million N95 respirators over the following 18 months to respond to the outbreak of the novel coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hhs.gov/about/news/2020/03/04/hhs-to-procure-n95-respirators-to-support-healthcare-workers-in-covid-19-outbreaks.html|title=HHS to Procure N95 Respirators to Support Healthcare Workers in COVID-19 Outbreaks|last=Division|first=News|date=2020-03-05|website=HHS.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n====March 5====\n\nNevada, Colorado, Tennessee, and Maryland announce their first cases, New Jersey announces a second presumptive case, while Washington announces 31 new cases.\n* [[Nevada]]: Public health officials in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]] report that state's first confirmed case of coronavirus: a man in his 50s in [[Clark County, Nevada|Clark County]] who recently traveled to Washington state and Texas.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fox5vegas.com/news/local/health-district-confirms-first-presumptive-positive-novel-coronavirus-case-in/article_ebbb3984-5f04-11ea-8137-338faf13fedc.html |title=Health District confirms first 'presumptive positive' novel coronavirus case in Clark County |last=Emerson |first=Elaine |date=March 5, 2020 |publisher=[[KVVU]] |access-date=March 5, 2020}}</ref> Also, public health officials announce a second confirmed case of coronavirus in [[Reno, Nevada|Reno]]. The new case, a man in his 50s, is in isolation at his home; the new case is linked to at least two other confirmed cases in [[Sonoma County, California]] and in [[Placer County, California]] among passengers who had been aboard the ''[[Grand Princess]]'' on a cruise from San Francisco to Mexico during the previous month.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.8newsnow.com/coronavirus/reno-man-tests-presumptive-positive-for-coronavirus-in-nevadas-second-case/ |title=Reno man tests 'presumptive positive' for coronavirus in Nevada's second case |last=Williams |first=Carolyn |date=March 6, 2020 |publisher=[[KLAS-TV|KLAS]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307134037/https://www.8newsnow.com/coronavirus/reno-man-tests-presumptive-positive-for-coronavirus-in-nevadas-second-case/ |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/nevada/articles/2020-03-06/reno-case-of-coronavirus-is-2nd-for-nevada |title=Reno case of coronavirus is 2nd for Nevada |date=March 6, 2020 |website=[[Associated Press|AP]] via [[US News and World Report]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307134122/https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/nevada/articles/2020-03-06/reno-case-of-coronavirus-is-2nd-for-nevada |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 6====\n\n[[File:2020-03-06 \u2014 Coronavirus \u2013 Flyers at Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport wearing facemasks.jpg|thumb|Airline passengers at [[Hartsfield-Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] wearing facemasks]]\n\nTen states report their first case of coronavirus: Hawaii, Utah, Nebraska, Kentucky, Indiana, Minnesota, Connecticut, South Carolina, Pennsylvania, and Oklahoma. Many cases are associated with passengers from the ''Grand Princess'' cruise ship, which is being held off the California coast near San Francisco. Testing on the ship reveals 21 positives. The day also sees 6{{nbsp}}deaths reported. Four are reported from Washington, by the hospital that treated patients from the LifeCare long-term care facility. Two are reported from Florida, and represent the third state (after Washington and California) with reported deaths. This brings the total deaths to 18, 15 in Washington, 1{{nbsp}}in California, and 2{{nbsp}}in Florida.\n\n<!--Cases on the Diamond Princess were considered separate from both the United Kingdom and Japan, and it appears the Grand Princess may have deliberately stayed outside territorial waters, so perhaps it shouldn't be included under California (or even the United States), especially since many other states have related cases.-->\n* ''Grand Princess'': Twenty-one passengers on the ''Grand Princess'' cruise ship test positive for the coronavirus, 19 staff and 2{{nbsp}}passengers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486394-pence-says-21-people-on-cruise-ship-off-california-have-coronavirus |title=Pence says 21 people on cruise ship off California tested positive for coronavirus |last=Swanson |first=Ian |date=March 6, 2020 |website=TheHill |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307025248/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486394-pence-says-21-people-on-cruise-ship-off-california-have-coronavirus |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* Arizona: Public health officials announce the state's third case and first community transmission case in a [[Pinal County, Arizona|Pinal County]] woman.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maricopa.gov/CivicAlerts.aspx?AID=1015 |title=Presumptive Positive Case of COVID-19 Identified in Pinal County. The case may signal community spread in Arizona |date=n.d. |website=Maricopa County, AZ |url-status=live |access-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Connecticut]]: Governor [[Ned Lamont]] confirm his state's first case of coronavirus in a hospital employee, a New York resident who is currently under self-quarantine back home in Westchester County, New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.courant.com/coronavirus/hc-br-connecticut-coronavirus-case-20200306-fxdj5smkgnf3jmgiuhn2coq22q-story.html |title=Gov. Lamont says Connecticut's first coronavirus case is an employee at Danbury Hospital who is now under self-quarantine |last=Fawcett |first=Zach Murdock, Alex Putterman, Eliza |website=courant.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307015150/https://www.courant.com/coronavirus/hc-br-connecticut-coronavirus-case-20200306-fxdj5smkgnf3jmgiuhn2coq22q-story.html |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* Hawaii: Governor [[David Ige]] announces its first case of coronavirus, a resident that was a passenger of the ''Grand Princess'' which stopped in Hawaii in late February.<ref name=\"hawaii.1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/gov-ige-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-hawaii/ |title=VIDEO: Hawaii resident, passenger aboard Grand Princess confirmed as first coronavirus case in Hawaii |date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307193138/https://www.khon2.com/coronavirus-2/gov-ige-confirms-first-case-of-coronavirus-in-hawaii/ |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Indiana]]: The state reports its first case in an [[Indianapolis]] man who returned from travel to Boston.<ref>{{cite news |title=Indiana has 1st illness linked to coronavirus outbreak |url=https://apnews.com/85a65282ef8f2ca99ef4fab42b7da374 |accessdate=20 March 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=6 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320105659/https://apnews.com/85a65282ef8f2ca99ef4fab42b7da374 |archive-date=March 20, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Kentucky]]: Governor [[Andy Beshear]] confirms the states first case, a [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] resident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/state/kentucky/article240970991.html |title=First case of Coronavirus confirmed in Kentucky, governor says |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306224123/https://www.kentucky.com/news/state/kentucky/article240970991.html |archive-date=March 6, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/louisville/news/2020/03/06/first-kentucky-coronavirus-case-confirmed.html |title=First Kentucky coronavirus case confirmed |date=March 6, 2020 |access-date=March 7, 2020 |publisher=Louisville Business First}}</ref>\n* [[Minnesota]]: announces its first presumptive case, an elderly person, living in [[Ramsey County, Minnesota|Ramsey County]], who had been on a cruise ship recently.<!--The official health department source does not state which cruise ship he was a passenger of, though it strongly suggests it was the Grand Princess by stating that it was a \"cruise ship with a known COVID-19 case\" (rather than \"many cases\" or something similar, as the seriousness of the Grand Princess cluster was not as well known at the time).--><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid19030620.html |title=News release: Headline |website=health.state.mn.us |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308144422/https://www.health.state.mn.us/news/pressrel/2020/covid19030620.html |archive-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> The patient is reported to be in quarantine in their home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486392-minnesota-reports-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case |title=Minnesota reports first presumptive coronavirus case |date=2020-03-06 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307045918/https://thehill.com/policy/healthcare/486392-minnesota-reports-first-presumptive-coronavirus-case |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* Nebraska: Governor [[Pete Ricketts]] announces the first presumptive positive case of coronavirus in Nebraska, a woman in her 30s from [[Douglas County, Nebraska|Douglas County]] who came back from England at the end of February.<ref name=\"nebraska.1\">{{cite web |url=https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/first-presumptive-positive-case-coronavirus-2019-reported-nebraska-dhhs |title=First Presumptive Positive Case of Coronavirus 2019 Reported to Nebraska DHHS |website=governor.nebraska.gov |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307055941/https://governor.nebraska.gov/press/first-presumptive-positive-case-coronavirus-2019-reported-nebraska-dhhs |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> She was initially hospitalized at [[Methodist Hospital (Omaha, Nebraska)|Methodist Hospital]], and was being transferred to the Biocontainment Unit at the University of Nebraska Medical Center after her test result came back positive.<ref name=\"nebraska.1\" />\n* North Carolina: Public health officials announce a second confirmed case of coronavirus in a man in [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]] who had recently traveled to Italy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ncdhhs.gov/news/press-releases/north-carolina-identifies-second-case-covid-19 |title=North Carolina Identifies Second Case of COVID-19 |date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307051953/https://www.ncdhhs.gov/news/press-releases/north-carolina-identifies-second-case-covid-19 |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article240915536.html |title=New coronavirus case diagnosed in North Carolina, officials say |last=Banov |first=Jessica |last2=Johnson |first2=Anna |date=March 6, 2020 |website=[[The News & Observer]], Raleigh, N.C. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307071415/https://www.newsobserver.com/news/local/article240915536.html |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Oklahoma]]: Officials announce its first confirmed case of coronavirus in a [[Tulsa County, Oklahoma|Tulsa County]] man who had recently traveled to Italy.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kjrh.com/news/local-news/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-tulsa-county |title=First Case of Coronavirus Confirmed in Tulsa County |date=March 6, 2020 |publisher=KJRH |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307143525/https://www.kjrh.com/news/local-news/first-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-tulsa-county |archive-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* Pennsylvania: Governor [[Tom Wolf]] announces the first two confirmed cases of coronavirus in [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Delaware County]] and in [[Wayne County, Pennsylvania|Wayne County]].\n* Rhode Island: The state confirms its third case, a woman who had contact with a positive case in New York in late February.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ri.gov/press/view/37858 |title=RIDOH's State Health Laboratories Identifies Third Case of COVID-19 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309185220/https://www.ri.gov/press/view/37858 |archive-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[South Carolina]] reports two presumptive cases in [[Kershaw County]] and [[Charleston County]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.live5news.com/2020/03/07/dhec-investigating-two-possible-cases-novel-coronavirus-south-carolina/ |title=DHEC investigating two possible cases of coronavirus in South Carolina |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 7====\n\nVirginia,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.13newsnow.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-virginia/291-e5e3c430-be8d-45d7-b858-859fba98a01d |title=First coronavirus case confirmed in Virginia |last=136News Now Staff |date=March 7, 2020 |website=136News Now |publisher=[[WVEC|WVEC-TV]] |location=[[Hampton, Virginia]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308192640/https://www.13newsnow.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/first-coronavirus-case-confirmed-in-virginia/291-e5e3c430-be8d-45d7-b858-859fba98a01d |archive-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> Kansas, Missouri, and Washington, D.C.<ref name=\"DC\">{{Cite news |last=Hahn |first=Fritz |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2020/03/05/dc-coronavirus-tourism/ |title=Coronavirus closes Smithsonian museums, cancels some National Cherry Blossom Festival events |work=Going Out Guide |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313190830/https://www.washingtonpost.com/dc-md-va/2020/03/05/dc-coronavirus-tourism/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |quote=The District announced its first confirmed case of the coronavirus that causes covid-19 on March 7. On March 11, Mayor Muriel E. Bowser declared a state of emergency in the District, and the D.C. Health Department recommended that \"nonessential mass gatherings\" of more than 1,000 people should be canceled or postponed until March 31.}}</ref> announces its first cases. A new death is reported for March{{nbsp}}7 in Washington. This brings the total confirmed US deaths due to coronavirus to 19, 16 in Washington, 1{{nbsp}}in California, and 2{{nbsp}}in Florida. In Pennsylvania, Governor Tom Wolf announces two new positive cases in [[Montgomery County, Pennsylvania|Montgomery County]]; both cases are related to travel within the United States.<ref>{{Cite news |last=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |url=https://6abc.com/health/2-montco-residents-test-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19/5993654/ |title=2 Montgomery County residents test presumptive positive for COVID-19 bringing state total to 4 |date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308165356/https://6abc.com/health/2-montco-residents-test-presumptive-positive-for-covid-19/5993654/ |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |publisher=[[WPVI-TV|WPVI]] |location=Media, PA}}</ref>\n\n====March 8====\n\n[[Iowa]] and [[Vermont]] report their first cases of infection with the coronavirus. Three new deaths were reported in WA. This brought the total confirmed US deaths due to coronavirus to 22: 19 in Washington, 1{{nbsp}}in California, and 2{{nbsp}}in Florida.\n* Hawaii: Second case is reported by Governor David Ige and State health officials is an elderly man who tested positive after returning from travel to Washington state earlier in the month. He is hospitalized and in isolation at Kaiser Permanente' Moanalua medical facility.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pang |first=Gordon |url=https://www.staradvertiser.com/2020/03/08/breaking-news/2nd-hawaii-resident-tests-positive-for-covid-19/ |title=Elderly man who recently traveled to Washington state becomes Hawaii's second coronavirus case |date=March 8, 2020 |work=Honolulu Star Advertiser |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Indiana: Second and third cases are reported, both in [[Hendricks County, Indiana|Hendricks County]]. The third case is an elementary student, resulting in recommendation from Hendricks County Health Department for closure of Hickory Elementary school for two weeks beginning March 9. This is the first school closing to occur in Indiana due to the current outbreak.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theindychannel.com/coronavirus/second-case-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-indiana-is-in-hendricks-county |title=Second case of coronavirus confirmed in Indiana is in Hendricks County |date=March 8, 2020 |access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.wishtv.com/news/local-news/avon-elementary-student-tests-positive-for-coronavirus/ |title=Avon elementary student tests positive for coronavirus |date=March 8, 2020 |access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n* Iowa: Governor [[Kim Reynolds]] confirmed the state's first three positive cases in [[Johnson County, Iowa|Johnson County]].\n* Minnesota: The state of Minnesota reports a new case in [[Carver County]] and a total of 2{{nbsp}}cases in Minnesota. The patient experienced symptoms on March 2, and is in the 50\u201359 age group. Thus far, both cases have been associated with travel.<ref name=\"StarT Carver Co.\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-reports-second-covid-19-case/568614092/?refresh=true |title=Minnesota reports second coronavirus case, this one in Carver County |work=Star Tribune |access-date=March 8, 2020 |issue=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n* South Carolina: four more presumptive positive cases, for a total of six. One recently traveled to Italy, two are connected to a previous case, and one is of unknown origin.\n* Vermont: Vermont health officials announced the state's first \"presumptive positive\" case in [[Bennington County, Vermont|Bennington County]].\n\n====March 9====\n\nOhio governor [[Mike DeWine]] declares a state of emergency after Ohio reports its first cases of COVID-19.<ref name=\"10TV STATE OF EMERGENCY\">{{cite web |url=https://www.10tv.com/article/3-confirmed-cases-coronavirus-ohio-dewine-declares-state-emergency-2020-mar |title=3 confirmed cases of coronavirus in Ohio; DeWine declares State of Emergency |date=March 9, 2020 |website=10TV}}</ref> As of March 9, Alabama, Alaska, Idaho, Maine, Michigan, Mississippi, New Mexico, North Dakota, South Dakota, and West Virginia have no cases, while Montana, Delaware, Wyoming and Arkansas have suspected cases. Washington reports 3{{nbsp}}new deaths and California 1, bringing the number of US coronavirus deaths to 26.\n\nIt is reported that the Trump administration, without explanation, postponed the [[Director of National Intelligence]]'s (DNI) annual ''[[US World Wide Threat Assessment]]'' which warns that the U.S. remains unprepared for a global pandemic. The office of the DNI was scheduled to deliver the ''Assessment'' to the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Intelligence Committee]] on February 12.<ref>John Walcott [https://time.com/5799765/intelligence-report-pandemic-dangers The Trump Administration Is Stalling an Intel Report That Warns the U.S. Isn't Ready for a Global Pandemic] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313034152/https://time.com/5799765/intelligence-report-pandemic-dangers/ |date=March 13, 2020 }} March 9, 2020 TIME.com</ref>\n\n* Indiana: A case is reported in [[Noble County, Indiana|Noble County]], the state's 4th.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.indystar.com/story/news/health/2020/03/09/coronavirus-indiana-total-number-cases-state-now-4/5000639002/ |title=Person in northeast Indiana tests positive for coronavirus, bringing state total to 4 |date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310055242/https://www.indystar.com/story/news/health/2020/03/09/coronavirus-indiana-total-number-cases-state-now-4/5000639002/ |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* Iowa: Five new presumptive positive cases are announced, bringing the statewide total to eight. Governor [[Kim Reynolds]] signed a Proclamation of Disaster Emergency.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kwwl.com/2020/03/09/kim-reynolds-signs-disaster-proclamation-due-to-the-coronavirus/ |title=Kim Reynolds signs disaster proclamation due to the coronavirus |date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310152524/https://kwwl.com/2020/03/09/kim-reynolds-signs-disaster-proclamation-due-to-the-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Kentucky: Governor Andy Beshear confirms two new cases bringing the state's total to six.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wkyt.com/content/news/SPECIAL-REPORT-Gov-Beshear-giving-update-on-coronavirus-cases-568624101.html |title=Two new coronavirus cases confirmed in Kentucky, total now six |date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313175426/https://www.wkyt.com/content/news/SPECIAL-REPORT-Gov-Beshear-giving-update-on-coronavirus-cases-568624101.html |archive-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Missouri: St. Louis County Executive Dr. Sam Page reports that the father and younger sister of the state's first coronavirus patient violated a self-quarantine order, attending a father-daughter function for her high school, [[Villa Duchesne and Oak Hill School|Villa Duchesne]], at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Clayton. The pair also attended a party for students from both Villa and the [[John Burroughs School]] before heading to the hotel. Villa cancels classes following the announcement, and the Burroughs students in attendance at the party were asked to stay home from school until further notice; they are ultimately cleared by medical professionals in consultation with the school later the same week, and the Ritz-Carlton was to undergo substantial cleaning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/health-med-fit/coronavirus/family-of-missouri-s-first-coronavirus-patient-broke-self-quarantine/article_94fe6bf6-f679-5b88-870c-18c5f79d019b.html |title=Family of Missouri's first coronavirus patient broke self quarantine, St. Louis County officials say |last=Munz |first=Michele |website=STLtoday.com |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310140757/https://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/health-med-fit/coronavirus/family-of-missouri-s-first-coronavirus-patient-broke-self-quarantine/article_94fe6bf6-f679-5b88-870c-18c5f79d019b.html |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* North Carolina: Five new presumptively positive cases are reported in [[Wake County]]. According to NCDHHS, all five had traveled to Boston in late February to attend a conference. This brings the total number of cases in North Carolina to 7.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://wlos.com/news/local/5-new-presumptively-positive-cases-of-the-coronavirus-in-nc |title=5 new presumptively positive cases of the coronavirus in North Carolina |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The [[Ohio State University]] suspends face-to-face instruction until March 30.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/03/ohio-state-suspends-classes-until-march-30-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak |title=OHIO STATE SUSPENDS CLASSES UNTIL MARCH 30 DUE TO CORONAVIRUS OUTBREAK |last=Milnes |last2=Garrison |first2=Max |date=March 9, 2020 |website=thelantern.com |last3=Raudins |first3=Sam |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315065838/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/03/ohio-state-suspends-classes-until-march-30-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Governor Mike DeWine declares a state of emergency.<ref name=\"10TV STATE OF EMERGENCY\"/>\n* South Carolina: One additional presumptive positive case is reported, raising the total to 7.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestate.com/news/state/south-carolina/article241030266.html|title=Total number of coronavirus cases in South Carolina rises to 7|first1=Lucas|last1=Daprile|first2=Sarah|last2=Ellis|date=March 9, 2020|website=thestate.com|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315194749/https://www.thestate.com/news/state/south-carolina/article241030266.html|archive-date=March 15, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, there is a \"possible\" case at [[Clemson University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.counton2.com/health/coronavirus/clemson-health-officials-monitoring-possible-case-of-coronavirus/|title=Clemson health officials monitoring possible case of Coronavirus|date=March 9, 2020|website=counton2.com|access-date=March 20, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200320175954/https://www.counton2.com/health/coronavirus/clemson-health-officials-monitoring-possible-case-of-coronavirus/|archive-date=March 20, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====March 10====\n\n[[File:New Rochelle Containment Area March 2020.svg|right|thumb|Location of the [[New Rochelle]] Containment Area within [[Westchester County]], New York]]\n\nSouth Dakota and Michigan reports their first cases. Mitigation measures expanded in New York, Massachusetts and Washington with a transition to online classes for universities and colleges and with the first semi-containment zone announced in New York. Two new deaths were reported in Washington and one death each reported in California, New Jersey, and South Dakota. This brought the total US deaths to 31 (24 WA, 3{{nbsp}}CA, 2{{nbsp}}FL, 1{{nbsp}}NJ, 1{{nbsp}}SD).\n* Massachusetts: Governor [[Charlie Baker]] declared a state of emergency as the number of cases doubled overnight, to 92. 70 of the cases are related to a meeting at [[Biogen]] in February. [[Harvard University]] ordered its students to vacate the campus by Sunday, March 15.<ref>[https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/10/massachusetts-declares-emergency-as-coronavirus-cases-double-overnight-with-51-new-infections.html?recirc=taboolainternal Massachusetts declares emergency as coronavirus cases more than double overnight with 51 new infections] by Noah Higgins-Dunn, CNBC, 10 Mar 2020, retrieved 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n* Minnesota: A third case in the state is confirmed in [[Anoka County, Minnesota|Anoka County]]. The individual is in the 30\u201339-year-old range and had no reported underlying conditions. The resident is in critical condition. According to health officials, the case was not transmitted in the state and there is no evidence that the virus is spreading from person to person in Minnesota. [[Tim Walz|Gov. Tim Walz]] signed a $21&nbsp;million bill for funding COVID-19 preparedness.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-confirms-third-covid-19-case-patient-is-hospitalized-in-critical-condition/568672732/ |title=Minnesota confirms third coronavirus case; patient is hospitalized in critical condition |website=Star Tribune |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311144250/http://www.startribune.com/minnesota-confirms-third-covid-19-case-patient-is-hospitalized-in-critical-condition/568672732/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[South Dakota]]: Health officials announce the state's first five confirmed cases and one death. The lone death tested positive for COVID-19, but the cause of death is still being investigated.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/first-presumptive-positive-coronavirus-case-in-south-dakota/ |title=5 Coronavirus cases, one death in South Dakota |date=March 10, 2020 |access-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312035323/https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/first-presumptive-positive-coronavirus-case-in-south-dakota/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 11====\n\nConfirmed coronavirus cases in the United States surpass 1,100.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html |title=U.S. Cases of Coronavirus Surpass 1,000; British Health Minister Is Infected |work=The New York Times |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310234022/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/10/world/coronavirus-news.html |archive-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Arkansas, Delaware, Mississippi, New Mexico, North Dakota and Wyoming reported their first cases. More universities and colleges suspend classes or move to remote-access teaching. Washington governor [[Jay Inslee]] orders a halt to all gatherings of greater than 250 in three counties, while Ohio governor [[Mike DeWine]] orders all public gatherings of more than 1,000 people to be banned statewide. Five new deaths are reported in Washington and one death in California. This brings the total US deaths to 37 (29 WA, 4{{nbsp}}CA, 2{{nbsp}}FL, 1{{nbsp}}NJ, 1{{nbsp}}SD).\n* Connecticut: Several towns in Connecticut announce schools will close for at least two weeks beginning March 12, including [[New Canaan, Connecticut|New Canaan]], where the state's third case was confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/new-canaan-schools-to-close-for-14-days-due-to-coronavirus/2236728/ |title=New Canaan Schools to Close for 14 Days Due to Coronavirus |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Florida: A man wearing a mask and gloves with symptoms who knowingly tested positive for Coronavirus boards a [[JetBlue]] plane from [[JFK Airport]] with his knowing wife to [[PBI Airport]] in [[West Palm Beach, FL]], potentially exposing both airports and an entire plane to the virus. Despite this, Florida officials release all passengers without requiring isolation or testing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wptv.com/news/region-c-palm-beach-county/west-palm-beach/health-department-investigating-medical-situation-on-flight-to-pbia |title=Passenger who arrived at Palm Beach International Airport tests positive for coronavirus |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=WPTV |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312120923/https://www.wptv.com/news/region-c-palm-beach-county/west-palm-beach/health-department-investigating-medical-situation-on-flight-to-pbia |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* Indiana: The state had 5 more cases, bringing the total to 11.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/indiana/articles/2020-03-11/4-new-covid-19-cases-in-indiana-state-now-has-10-cases |title=Archived copy |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313024322/https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/indiana/articles/2020-03-11/4-new-covid-19-cases-in-indiana-state-now-has-10-cases |archive-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[University of Notre Dame]] announce that in-person classes will be suspended and moved online until at least April 13.<ref name=\"ND\">{{cite web |url=https://news.nd.edu/news/notre-dame-switches-to-online-after-canceling-in-person-classes/ |title=Notre Dame switches to online after canceling in-person classes |last=Dame |first=Marketing Communications: Web // University of Notre |website=Notre Dame News}}</ref>\n* [[Maine]]: The [[University of Maine]] in [[Orono, Maine|Orono]] announce that in-person classes will be cancelled for the remainder of the semester beginning March 23, and that all classes will be transitioned to online only. In addition, all students living on campus were required to be moved out by March 22.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://umaine.edu/emergency/coronavirus/ |title=UMaine/UMM coronavirus response frequently asked questions, March 12\u2014Emergency Information\u2014University of Maine |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Minnesota: The [[University of Minnesota]] announce that all in-person classes will be suspended until at least April{{nbsp}}1 following spring break.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/11/coronavirus-minnesota-university-classes-suspended-canceled/ |title=Coronavirus in Minnesota: U Of M, UW-Madison Among Universities Suspending In-Person Classes |date=March 11, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312180101/https://minnesota.cbslocal.com/2020/03/11/coronavirus-minnesota-university-classes-suspended-canceled/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Two more cases were confirmed, bringing the total number of cases to five.<ref name=\":6\">{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |title=Situation Update for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19)\u2014Minnesota Dept. of Health |website=health.state.mn.us |access-date=March 17, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309021508/https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Mayo Clinic]] in [[Rochester, MN|Rochester]] began \"drive-through testing\" for the virus, though patients still needed to be approved to be tested by telephone screening.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.postbulletin.com/life/health/mayo-clinic-starts-drive-thru-testing-for-covid/article_0087a856-63e3-11ea-be76-c7558f932526.html |title=Mayo Clinic starts drive-thru testing for COVID-19 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315124156/https://www.postbulletin.com/life/health/mayo-clinic-starts-drive-thru-testing-for-covid/article_0087a856-63e3-11ea-be76-c7558f932526.html |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Missouri: [[Washington University in Saint Louis]] announces a switch to online classes until at least late April and asked undergraduates to go home by March 15. [[University of Missouri|University of Missouri's Columbia campus]] cancels classes March 12 and 13 and directs that in-person classes should be taught by other means for March 16 through 20 (prior to the March 21 through 29 spring recess).\n* Mississippi: Health officials report the state's first case, a man who had recently traveled to Florida.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/23,21819,341.html |title=Mississippi Reports First Positive Case of Coronavirus\u2014Mississippi State Department of Health |website=msdh.ms.gov |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312133123/https://msdh.ms.gov/msdhsite/_static/23,21819,341.html |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* New Mexico: Three presumptive positive cases, a couple in their 60s who recently traveled to Egypt and one in her 70s who recently traveled to the New York City area.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.krqe.com/health/coronavirus-new-mexico/three-presumptive-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-mexico/ |title=Three presumptive cases of coronavirus confirmed in New Mexico |publisher=KRQE |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311172039/https://www.krqe.com/health/coronavirus-new-mexico/three-presumptive-cases-of-coronavirus-confirmed-in-new-mexico/ |archive-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n* Oklahoma: [[NBA]] player [[Rudy Gobert]] tested positive for COVID-19 prior to the game between the [[Utah Jazz]] and the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] at [[Chesapeake Energy Arena]] in [[Oklahoma City]]. The game was postponed and the NBA announced that the [[2019\u201320 NBA season]] would be suspended.\n* South Dakota: Three presumptive positive cases, bringing state total to eight.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/noem-to-hold-covid-19-news-conference-wednesday-afternoon/ |title=LATEST: CDC announces $4.6 million in COVID-19 funding to South Dakota; Noem to hold media briefing |website=KELOLAND |publisher=KELOLAND |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312034133/https://www.keloland.com/news/healthbeat/coronavirus/noem-to-hold-covid-19-news-conference-wednesday-afternoon/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident Trump said in an Oval Office address: \"The vast majority of Americans, the risk is very, very low.\"<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\nWHO Director-General Tedros stated the WHO \"made the assessment that COVID-19 can be characterized as a pandemic.\"<ref name=\"NPR_WHO1\"/>\n\n====March 12====\n\nTotal US cases passed 1,500. More universities and colleges transitioned to online attendance across the country. Public school closures are announced in Arkansas, Colorado, Connecticut, Kentucky, Maryland, Massachusetts, Michigan, New Mexico, Ohio, Utah, Virginia and Washington state. Georgia and Kansas report their first deaths and Washington state reports 2{{nbsp}}additional deaths. This brings the total US deaths to 41 (31 WA, 4{{nbsp}}CA, 2{{nbsp}}FL, 1{{nbsp}}NJ, 1{{nbsp}}SD, 1{{nbsp}}GA, 1{{nbsp}}KS).\n\nMost major sports leagues, including [[Major League Soccer|MLS]], the [[NHL]], and the [[National Lacrosse League]], announce the suspension of their seasons that are already in progress. The [[XFL (2020)|XFL]] terminates its [[2020 XFL season|inaugural season]], while [[Major League Baseball]] announces the cancellation of all remaining [[spring training]] games and delays the start of their [[2020 MLB season|2020 season]]. In addition, the [[NCAA]] cancels all postseason tournaments in their winter and spring sports, which includes the [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men's]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women's]] basketball tournaments, as well as the [[2020 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament|baseball]] and [[2020 NCAA Division I Softball Tournament|softball]] tournaments. The cancellation of the basketball tournament marks the first time the tournament will not be held due to unforeseen circumstances.\n* Alabama: Despite having no recorded cases in the state, the [[University of Alabama System]] as well as [[Auburn University]] both announced they are transitioning to online remote attendance when courses resume from spring break.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uasystem.edu/updated-interim-emergency-policy-for-ua-uab-and-uah/ |title=Updated Interim Emergency Policy for UA, UAB and UAH |publisher=University of Alabama System |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312225239/http://uasystem.edu/updated-interim-emergency-policy-for-ua-uab-and-uah/ |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ocm.auburn.edu/newsroom/news_articles/2020/03/121240-coronavirus-remote-transition.php |title=Auburn University to transition to remote instruction March 16 \u2013 April 10 |publisher=Auburn University |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200312193041/https://ocm.auburn.edu/newsroom/news_articles/2020/03/121240-coronavirus-remote-transition.php |archive-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n* Alaska: State officials announced the first positive case of coronavirus in the state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/13/first-positive-alaska-coronavirus-case-identified/ |title=First positive Alaska coronavirus case identified |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=Anchorage Daily News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313064058/https://www.adn.com/alaska-news/2020/03/13/first-positive-alaska-coronavirus-case-identified/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Colorado: The first school districts in the state, including [[Denver Public Schools]], announced closures. An employee at [[University of Colorado Boulder]] tested positive for coronavirus. The [[Colorado Department of Corrections]] suspended in-person visitation in state prisons. The state reported 11 new cases.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cpr.org/2020/03/12/colorado-coronavirus-updates-closures-testing-cases-school/ |title=Coronavirus in Colorado: What's going on today |last=Colorado Public Radio Staff |date=2020-03-12 |website=Colorado Public Radio |access-date=2020-03-17 }}{{Dead link|date=April 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* Connecticut: A number of school districts announced closures beginning on March 13 through at least March 27, including those in the cities of [[Bridgeport, Connecticut|Bridgeport]], [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], and [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]], among several others.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/weather/school-closings/ |title=School Closings\u2014Connecticut News, Local News, Weather, Traffic, Entertainment, Breaking News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101074233/https://www.nbcconnecticut.com/weather/school-closings/ |archive-date=January 1, 2020}}</ref>\n* Delaware: Governor [[John Carney (politician)|John Carney]] declared a state of emergency following the announcement of three more cases, connected with the University of Delaware.\n* Hawaii: The [[University of Hawaii]] announced classes at all campuses will be held online beginning March 23.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2020/03/12/uh-actions-address-covid-19/ |title=University of Hawaii actions to address COVID-19 pandemic &#124; University of Hawai\u02bbi System News |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313193051/https://www.hawaii.edu/news/2020/03/12/uh-actions-address-covid-19/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Indiana: Went from 11 to 12 cases. Gov. Holcomb Announces New Steps to Protect Public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://calendar.in.gov/site/gov/event/gov-holcomb-announces-new-steps-to-protect-public-from-covid-19/ |title=Gov. Holcomb Announces New Steps to Protect Public from COVID-19 |website=calendar.in.gov}}</ref>\n* Maine: Maine governor [[Janet Mills]] announced the state's first confirmed case of the virus, a woman in her 50s in [[Androscoggin County]]. The woman is said to be quarantined inside her home.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/maine-confirms-first-coronavirus-case |title=Maine confirms first coronavirus case, patient is quarantined at home |last=Hein |first=Alexandria |date=March 12, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Minnesota: The Minnesota Department of Health has confirmed nine total cases in the state, affecting [[Anoka County, Minnesota|Anoka]], [[Carver County, Minnesota|Carver]], [[Dakota County, Minnesota|Dakota]], [[Hennepin County, Minnesota|Hennepin]], [[Olmsted County, Minnesota|Olmsted]], [[Ramsey County, Minnesota|Ramsey]], and [[Stearns County, Minnesota|Stearns]] counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |title=Situation Update for Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309021508/https://www.health.state.mn.us/diseases/coronavirus/situation.html |archive-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* New Mexico: All public schools in the state will be closed for three weeks starting Monday, March 16.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.governor.state.nm.us/2020/03/12/new-mexico-schools-to-temporarily-close/ |title=New Mexico schools to temporarily close &#124; Office of the Governor\u2014Michelle Lujan Grisham |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313081615/https://www.governor.state.nm.us/2020/03/12/new-mexico-schools-to-temporarily-close/ |archive-date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n* Ohio: The Ohio State University suspends all face-to-face classes for the rest of the spring semester. Spring break is extended until March 22 so that faculty have time to prepare. Students living in residence halls are to begin moving out.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.thelantern.com/2020/03/university-announces-virtual-instruction-for-rest-of-semester-early-move-out-of-residence-halls/ |title=University Announces Virtual Instruction For Rest of Semester, Early Move-Out of Residence Halls |last=Long |first=Jack |last2=Milnes |first2=Owen |date=March 12, 2020 |website=thelantern.com |last3=Szilagy |first3=Sarah |last4=Raudins |first4=Sam |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317191452/https://www.thelantern.com/2020/03/university-announces-virtual-instruction-for-rest-of-semester-early-move-out-of-residence-halls/ |archive-date=March 17, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Mike DeWine is the first governor to announce statewide school closings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.axios.com/ohio-governor-bars-restaurants-coronavirus-26e4b6e3-7f65-4f6a-abf9-f3940220cc6f.html |title=States order bars and restaurants to close due to coronavirus |last=Basu |first=Zachary |website=Axios |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316084429/https://www.axios.com/ohio-governor-bars-restaurants-coronavirus-26e4b6e3-7f65-4f6a-abf9-f3940220cc6f.html |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Starting on March 16 all K-12 schools in Ohio will be closed for three weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbc4i.com/news/local-news/coronavirus-in-ohio-governor-orders-schools-to-take-extended-spring-breaks-starting-monday/ |title=Coronavirus in Ohio: Governor orders schools to take extended spring breaks starting Monday |date=March 12, 2020 |website=NBC4 WCMH-TV |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> DeWine also bans \"mass gatherings\" of 100 or more people.<ref name=\"CBS10 TIMELINE\">{{cite web|url=https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-barbershops-hair-and-nail-salons-ordered-close-amid-coronavirus-concerns-2020-mar|title=Ohio barbershops, hair and nail salons ordered to close amid coronavirus concerns|date=March 18, 2010|website=10tv.com|access-date=March 18, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318232922/https://www.10tv.com/article/ohio-barbershops-hair-and-nail-salons-ordered-close-amid-coronavirus-concerns-2020-mar|archive-date=March 18, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, HHS placed its first order of N95 respirators for healthcare workers of $4.8 million. However, the supplier contract required delivery to begin around the end of April. Former HHS Secretary [[Kathleen Sebelius]] stated: \"We basically wasted two months.\"<ref>Michael Biesecker ''[https://apnews.com/090600c299a8cf07f5b44d92534856bc US 'wasted' months before preparing for coronavirus pandemic]'' April 6, 2020 APNews.com</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2020/4/5/21208802/coronavirus-trump-ventilators-masks-march |title=Trump administration didn't order ventilators or masks until mid-March |publisher=Vox |date= |accessdate=2020-04-07}}</ref>\n\n====March 13====\n\nTotal U.S. cases passed 2,100. Colorado reported its first death,<ref>{{Cite news |last=Seaman |first=Jessica |url=https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/13/colorado-coronavirus-death/ |title=Colorado confirms first coronavirus death since outbreak hit state last week |date=2020-03-13 |work=The Denver Post |access-date=2020-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318054827/https://www.denverpost.com/2020/03/13/colorado-coronavirus-death/ |archive-date=March 18, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Florida and California both reported an additional death, and Washington state reported 6{{nbsp}}additional deaths. This brought the total number of deaths in the US to 50 (37 WA, 5{{nbsp}}CA, 3{{nbsp}}FL, 1{{nbsp}}NJ, 1{{nbsp}}SD, 1{{nbsp}}GA, 1{{nbsp}}KS, 1{{nbsp}}CO). The [[National Hockey League|NHL]] (National Hockey League) asked players to self-quarantine for a week or more in an attempt to save the season.<ref>[https://www.tsn.ca/nhl-urges-players-to-self-quarantine-to-help-save-season-1.1457233 NHL urges players to 'self-quarantine' to help save season] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317193559/https://www.tsn.ca/nhl-urges-players-to-self-quarantine-to-help-save-season-1.1457233 |date=March 17, 2020 }}, TSN, Frank Seravalli, March 13, 2020.</ref>\n\nLater that day, President [[Donald Trump]] took a COVID-19 test after coming into contact with several people who had contracted the disease and found to be negative.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-live-updates-house-passes-coronavirus-pandemic-stimulus/story?id=69593951 |title=Coronavirus live updates: Trump says he took test; travel ban extended to UK, Ireland |date=March 14, 2020 |work=ABC News |url-status=live |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314222831/https://abcnews.go.com/US/coronavirus-live-updates-house-passes-coronavirus-pandemic-stimulus/story?id=69593951 |archive-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/14/trump-coronavirus-paid-sick-leave-unemployment-testing |title=Trump says he took coronavirus test and expands travel ban to UK and Ireland |date=March 14, 2020 |work=The Guardian |url-status=live |access-date=March 18, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314224603/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/mar/14/trump-coronavirus-paid-sick-leave-unemployment-testing |archive-date=March 14, 2020 }}</ref> On March 13 the House passed an [https://www.congress.gov/bill/116th-congress/house-bill/6201?s=1&r=88 aid package] for workers and individuals that was supported by President Trump.<ref>[https://www.newsweek.com/40-house-republicans-reject-paid-sick-leave-combat-coronavirus-pandemic-1491988?fbclid=IwAR0uw1yoA7-J5VS5dScaZeuxdg5Jer5ApHfQZWIdTmfr24pgW7jHcjSweNA 40 HOUSE REPUBLICANS REJECT PAID SICK LEAVE TO COMBAT CORONAVIRUS PANDEMIC] BY RAMSEY TOUCHBERRY, Newsweek, 14 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nIn a March 13, 2020 report \"not for public distribution\", the [[United States Department of Health and Human Services]] (HHS) used the working assumptions for their response plan, that the COVID-19 \"pandemic will last 18 months or longer and could include multiple waves of illness\", and that resultant \"supply chain and transportation impacts\" would \"likely result in significant shortages\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernstein |first1=Leandra |title=Government report anticipates 18-month pandemic, 'significant shortages' |url=https://komonews.com/news/nation-world/government-report-anticipates-18-month-pandemic-significant-shortages |accessdate=March 24, 2020 |work=[[Sinclair Broadcast Group]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n* Alabama: First case announced in Montgomery County.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.waff.com/2020/03/13/governor-ivey-releases-statement-alabamas-first-confirmed-coronavirus-case/|title=WAFF48: First case of COVID-19 confirmed in Alabama|date=March 13, 2020|website=waff.com}}</ref>\n* Georgia: Governor Brian Kemp declared a public health emergency in the state of Georgia.<ref name=\":3a\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsbtv.com/news/georgia/gov-kemp-declare-public-health-emergency-call-special-session/F4ZAZ67SKZAC5ITRZGYGA5JKJE/ |title=Gov. Kemp declares public health emergency; calls for special session |last=WSBTV com News Staff |website=WSBTV |language=en-US |access-date=2020-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319210849/https://www.wsbtv.com/news/georgia/gov-kemp-declare-public-health-emergency-call-special-session/F4ZAZ67SKZAC5ITRZGYGA5JKJE/ |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Idaho]]: The state's first confirmed case of the virus was announced, a woman in her 50s who recently traveled to New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/idaho-confirms-first-covid-19-coronavirus-case/277-262de30b-ef00-40a2-b40e-43e26f0bb99b |title=Watch Live: First Idaho case of coronavirus confirmed, Gov. Brad Little to provide more details |last=Miller |first=Tyson |website=KTVB.com |publisher=KTVB |access-date=March 13, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314051016/https://www.ktvb.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/idaho-confirms-first-covid-19-coronavirus-case/277-262de30b-ef00-40a2-b40e-43e26f0bb99b |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Illinois: All schools are closed beginning Tuesday, March 17 through the end of March.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/all-illinois-schools-to-close-over-coronavirus-governor-announces/2236775/ |title=All Illinois Schools to Close Due to Coronavirus, Governor Announces |date=March 13, 2020 |website=NBC5 Chicago |access-date=March 15, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200315023607/https://www.nbcchicago.com/news/local/all-illinois-schools-to-close-over-coronavirus-governor-announces/2236775/ |archive-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Kentucky: First of Kentucky's COVID-19 patients to be declared fully recovered is discharged from University of Kentucky Medical Center.<ref name=\"Lexington Herald-Leader\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kentucky.com/news/health-and-medicine/article241173516.html |title=First Kentucky coronavirus patient is 'fully recovered,' discharged from UK hospital |website=kentucky.com |publisher=Lexington Herald-Leader |access-date=15 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316115904/https://www.kentucky.com/news/health-and-medicine/article241173516.html |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Minnesota: Governor Tim Walz declared a state of emergency and asked the state legislature to pass several emergency bills, including a bill to help speed up testing for the virus. He also urged that all events with 250 or more attendees be cancelled or postponed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/walz-declares-state-of-emergency-for-minnesota-urges-canceling-or-postponing-all-large-events/ |title=Walz declares state of emergency for Minnesota, urges canceling or postponing all large events |date=2020-03-13 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200314150905/https://www.minnpost.com/state-government/2020/03/walz-declares-state-of-emergency-for-minnesota-urges-canceling-or-postponing-all-large-events/ |archive-date=March 14, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Missouri: Two more presumptive positive cases were reported, bring the total number of cases up to 4. [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]] declares a state of emergency and bans gatherings larger than 250 people.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2020/03/13/st-louis-county-bans-events-of-more-than-250-people |title=St. Louis County Bans Events of More Than 250 People |last=Murphy |first=Doyle |website=Riverfront Times |access-date=March 14, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200313201005/https://www.riverfronttimes.com/newsblog/2020/03/13/st-louis-county-bans-events-of-more-than-250-people |archive-date=March 13, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* New Hampshire: Governor Christopher Sununu declares state of emergency in New Hampshire due to Covid-19. Six cases are confirmed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.nh.gov/news-media/orders-2020/documents/2020-04.pdf|title=Executive Order 2020-04\u2014An order declaring a state of emergency due to Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19)|last=Sununu|first=Christopher|date=March 13, 2020|website=State of New Hampshire Office of the Governor|url-status=live|archive-u