 of health care workers and other emergency workers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fox9.com/news/walz-schools-to-remain-open-for-children-of-health-care-workers-emergency-responders |title=Walz: Schools to remain open for children of health care workers, emergency responders |date=2020-03-15 |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200319210907/https://www.fox9.com/news/walz-schools-to-remain-open-for-children-of-health-care-workers-emergency-responders |archive-date=March 19, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> Teachers will be using this time to plan for a possibility of weeks of long-distance learning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/14/walz-minnesota-schools-closed-covid19 |title=Walz announces temporary closure of Minnesota K-12 public schools |access-date=March 16, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316125656/https://www.mprnews.org/story/2020/03/14/walz-minnesota-schools-closed-covid19 |archive-date=March 16, 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* New Hampshire: Governor Christopher Sununu orders all public K-12 schools to transition to remote learning effective Monday, March 16 through April 3, 2020, requiring remote learning to begin by March 23, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.governor.nh.gov/news-media/emergency-orders/documents/emergency-order-1.pdf|title=Emergency Order 1\u2014Temporary remote instruction and support for public K-12 school districts|last=Sununu|first=Christopher|date=March 15, 2020|website=State of New Hampshire, Office of the Governor|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* North Carolina: [[Mecklenburg County, North Carolina|Mecklenburg]] County which encompassed the city of Charlotte declared a state of emergency in the county after 2{{nbsp}}more new cases are found in the county, bringing the total in the county to 4{{nbsp}}and the total statewide to 33.<ref name=\":11a\">{{cite web |url=https://www.charlotteobserver.com/news/local/articl