{"title_page": "Farouq Brigades", "text_new": "{{infobox war faction\n|name         = Farouq Brigades\n|native_name  = \u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0642\n|native_name_lang = Ar\n|war          = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n|image        = [[File:Farouq Brigades.jpg|200px]]\n|caption      = Logo of the Farouq Brigades\n|active       = June 2011 \u2013 2014 (central organization, remnants remained active until 2017)\n|ideology     = [[Sunni]] [[Islamism]]\n|leaders      = Abdul Razzaq Tlass <small>(October 2011 \u2013 6 October 2012)</small><br/> Osama Juneidi (Abu Sayeh) <ref name=FreedomfighterCannibals>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/freedom-fighters-cannibals-the-truth-about-syrias-rebels-8662618.html|title=Freedom fighters? Cannibals? The truth about Syria\u2019s rebels|author=Aron Lund|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=17 June 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Lund\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/10/15/holy_warriors|title=Holy Warriors|last=Lund|first=Aron|publisher=[[Foreign Policy]]|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> {{Clear}} Taleb al-Dayekh<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/72824-report-fsa-shells-hizbullah-positions-in-lebanon-syria|title=FSA Denies Shelling Hizbullah Positions in Lebanon, Syria|publisher=Naharnet|date=21 February 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n|groups       =\n|headquarters = [[Homs]]\n|area         = [[Homs Governorate]], [[Syria]]<br/>[[Aleppo Governorate]], [[Syria]]\n|strength     = 14,000<ref name=FreedomfighterCannibals/>\u201320,000<ref name=bbc-20130514>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-22521161|title=Gruesome Syria video pinpoints West's dilemma|author=Jonathan Marcus|publisher=BBC|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> (own claim) <small>(May\u2013June 2013)</small>\n|partof       = [[Free Syrian Army]]<br/>[[Syrian Islamic Liberation Front]] <small>(2012-2013)</small><br/>[[Ahrar al-Sham]] & [[Tahrir al-Sham]]\n|split_from   = [[Khalid ibn al-Walid Brigade|Khalid ibn al-Walid Battalion]]\n|next         = \n|allies       = [[Suqour al-Sham]]<br/>[[Liwa al-Islam]]<ref name=Lund/><br/>[[Liwa Thuwwar al-Raqqa]]<br/>[[People's Protection Units]]<ref name=ac>{{cite web|url=http://the-arab-chronicle.com/dialogue-collaboration-syria-kurds-rebels/ |title=A new dialogue and collaboration in northern Syria between kurds and rebels |publisher=The Arab Chronicle |access-date=22 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012110623/http://the-arab-chronicle.com/dialogue-collaboration-syria-kurds-rebels/ |archive-date=12 October 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|opponents    =  [[Syrian Armed Forces]]<br/> [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n|battles      = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[2012 Homs offensive]]\n* [[Battle of al-Qusayr (2012)]]\n* [[Siege of Northern Homs]]\n* [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u201313)|Battle of Aleppo]]\n* [[Al-Qusayr offensive]]\n** [[Battle of al-Qusayr (2013)]]\n* [[Battle of Ma'loula]]\n* [[Raqqa campaign (2012\u201313)]]\n* [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013-present)]]<ref name=ac/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Farouq Brigades''' ({{lang-ar|\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0642}}), also spelt '''Farooq''' and '''Farook''', was an armed rebel organisation formed by a number of [[Homs]] based members of the [[Free Syrian Army]] early in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\"Abouzeid\">{{cite news|title=Syria\u2019s Up-and-Coming Rebels: Who Are the Farouq Brigades?|url=http://world.time.com/2012/10/05/syrias-up-and-coming-rebels-who-are-the-farouq-brigades-2/print/|last=Abouzeid |first=Rania|publisher=[[Time Magazine]]|date=5 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The group rapidly expanded in size and prominence in 2012,<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/> before suffering internal splits and battlefield reversals in 2013 that greatly reduced its influence.<ref name=\"fp211113\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2013/11/21/rebels_inc|title=Rebels, Inc.|publisher=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> By 2014, the group was largely defunct, with member factions joining other rebel groups.<ref name=huffpo11april/> The brigades were named Farouq after [[Omar bin al-Khattab]], a [[Sahaba]] (companion) of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] and the second [[Caliph]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Farouq Brigades emerged from the central city of [[Homs]] just months into the [[Syrian Civil War]]. Its beginnings are as a subunit of the [[Khalid ibn al-Walid Brigade]], a group of defectors from the [[Syrian Army]] that announced its formation in June 2011 and engaged in clashes with members of the Syrian security forces in Homs and [[Al-Rastan]]. The group started out with 3,000+ fighters. During the second half of 2011, Farouq was active in Homs, particularly the [[Baba Amr]] neighborhood. It was led by a defector, Lieutenant Abdul Razaq Tlass, who was a nephew of the former Syrian Defense Minister [[Mustafa Tlass]].<ref name=\"Holliday\">{{cite web|title=Syria\u2019s Armed Opposition |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Syrias_Armed_Opposition.pdf|last=Holliday|first=Joseph|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> The apparent success of Farouq in holding territory in Baba Amr led to the Syrian government escalating their use of force in an [[2012 Homs offensive|offensive in early 2012]], causing heavy casualties amongst the rebels and forcing their retreat into the Homs countryside and the towns of [[Al-Qusayr, Syria|Al-Qusayr]] and Al-Rastan.<ref name=\"Holliday\"/>\n\nIn the following months, Farouq absorbed preexisting rebel units and formed new ones across Syria, from [[Daraa]] in the south near the Jordanian border to the Farouq al-Shemal (Northern Farouq) which controlled some of the border posts in the north with Turkey.<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/>\n\nIn September 2012, a large number of [[Islamist]] rebel brigades, including the Farouq Brigades and the [[Suqour al-Sham Brigade|Suquor al-Sham]] formed the [[Syrian Islamic Liberation Front]], under the leadership of Suquor al-Sham commander Ahmed Abu Issa. Abu Issa claimed the new Front had more than 40,000 fighters, and aimed to establish a state with an ''Islamic reference''.<ref name=\"reuters111012\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/11/us-syria-crisis-rebels-idUSBRE89A0Y920121011|title=Syria's Islamist rebels join forces against Assad|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=15 May 2014|date=11 October 2012}}</ref> In May 2013, the [[BBC]] gave estimate of 20,000 fighters.<ref name=bbc-20130514/> In November 2013, the SILF was superseded by a new rebel coalition called the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]]; however, Farouq was not a member of this grouping.<ref name=\"BBC22Nov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-25053525|title=Leading Syrian rebel groups form new Islamic Front|publisher=BBC|date=22 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology and funding ==\nJeffrey White, a former U.S. defense intelligence officer with the [[Washington Institute for Near East Policy]] and Joseph Holliday, a research analyst with the [[Institute for the Study of War]] consider the Farouq Brigade to be \u201cmoderately Islamist\u201d \u2013 that is, neither [[secular]] nor [[Salafis]].<ref name=bbc-20130514/> While many of their fighters wear [[Jihadist]]-style black headbands and beards, it is unclear how much of this is genuine belief and how much is to secure additional funding from Islamist donors.<ref name=\"Ackerman\">{{cite web|title=Syrian Rebels Burn Down a Marijuana Field on Facebook|url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2012/10/syrian-rebel-facebook/|last=Ackerman|first=Spencer|publisher=[[Wired Magazine]]|date=16 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFarouq has their own [[public relations]] wing which film their battlefield operations and upload them to [[YouTube]] and [[Facebook]] with their groups logo. These clips are used for fundraising from Syrians, donors in Gulf states, western sources and Islamist groups.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battle for Syria: on the ground with the Farouk brigade|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/battle-for-syria-on-the-ground-with-the-farouk-brigade|publisher=[[Channel 4 News]]|date=11 September 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{see also|Human rights violations during the Syrian Civil War#Free Syrian Army and other armed opposition fighters}}\nIn April 2012, the Farouq Brigades was accused of collecting [[jizyah]], or taxes imposed on non-Muslims living under Muslim rule, in Christian areas of Homs province. However, the group denied this and the [[Institute for the Study of War]] said that \"the accusation is likely from the Assad regime\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria\u2019s Maturing Insurgency|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Syrias_MaturingInsurgency_21June2012.pdf|last=Holliday|first=Joseph|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> There were also reports that the group had expelled 90% of the Christian population of Homs City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fides.org/aree/news/newsdet.php?idnews=31228&lan=eng|title=Abuse of the opposition forces, \"ethnic cleansing\" of Christians in Homs, where Jesuits remains|agency=Agenzia Fides|access-date=15 May 2014|date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127140505/http://www.fides.org/aree/news/newsdet.php?idnews=31228&lan=eng|archive-date=27 January 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fides.org/en/news/31262?idnews=31262&lan=eng#.U3TibHaGe0o|title=The Jesuits: \"Christians have fled from Homs, not thrown out by Islamists\"|agency=Agenzia Fides|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> However, [[Jesuits]] in Homs disputed the cause of the exodus, and said that Christians were not targeted specifically, but fled the city on their own initiative because of the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/news/headlines/index.cfm?storyid=13804|title=Are Islamists targeting Christians in Homs? Catholic groups dispute cause of exodus|publisher=catholicCulture.org|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> According to interviews made by ''McClatchy Newspapers'' of refugees in Lebanon, there was no targeting of Christians because of their religion. Rather, a number of government-affiliated Christians were seized by the Farouq Brigades, which led to some Christians fleeing the area.{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn August 2012, Lieutenant Abdul Razzaq Tlass, one of the Farouq Brigades top leaders, was implicated in a [[sex scandal]] when video was posted to [[YouTube]] appearing to show him having [[cybersex]] with a woman through [[Skype]]. Tlass and others claimed the video was a fabrication by the Syrian Government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Syrian Rebel Leader Accuses Regime Of Fabricating Scandalous Video|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2012/08/20/159375256/syrian-rebel-leader-accuses-regime-of-fabricating-scandalous-video|last=Marrouch|first=Rima|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=15 May 2014|date=20 August 2012}}</ref> Nevertheless, by October 2012, Tlass was replaced as commander by Abu Sayeh Juneidi.<ref name=\"Lund\"/>\n\nIn September 2012, the northern branch of the Farouq Brigades was accused of kidnapping and killing Abu Mohamad al-Absi, a Syrian Jihadist who led a group of foreign fighters. The local Farouq Brigades leader said the foreign fighters had ignored their demands to leave the Bab al-Hawa border post. He said that al-Absi had \"raised the al-Qaeda flag, and al-Qaeda is not welcomed by us\".<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/>\n\nIn May 2013, a video was posted on the internet showing rebel commander Abu Sakkar cutting organs from the dead body of a Syrian soldier and putting one of them in his mouth, \"as if he is taking a bite out of it\". He called rebels to follow his example and terrorize the Alawite sect, which mostly backs Assad. [[Human Rights Watch]] confirmed the authenticity of the footage, and stated that \"The mutilation of the bodies of enemies is a war crime. But the even more serious issue is the very rapid descent into sectarian rhetoric and violence\". It said that Abu Sakkar appears to be a commander of the \"Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade\". The BBC called it an offshoot or sub-unit of the Farouq Brigades, saying that \"the Farouq Brigade appears to be actually a complex of sub-units with a tangled pedigree\".<ref name=bbc-20130514/> Human Rights Watch said \"It is not known whether the Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade operates within the command structure of the Free Syrian Army\". The incident was condemned by the FSA's Chief of Staff and the Syrian National Coalition said that the commander would be put on trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2013/05/13/syria-brigade-fighting-homs-implicated-atrocities |title=Syria: Brigade Fighting in Homs Implicated in Atrocities|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-22519770|title=Outrage at Syrian rebel shown 'eating soldier's heart'|publisher=BBC|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The rebel Supreme Military Council called for Abu Sakkar's arrest, saying it wants him \"dead or alive\". Abu Sakkar said that the mutilation was revenge. He claimed he found a video on the soldier's cellphone in which the soldier sexually abuses a woman and her two daughters,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://world.time.com/2013/05/14/we-will-slaughter-all-of-them-an-interview-with-the-man-behind-the-syrian-atrocity-video/?iid=gs-main-lead|title=\"Exclusive: \"We Will Slaughter All of Them.\" The Rebel Behind The Syrian Atrocity Video|publisher=Time|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> along with other videos showing Assad loyalists raping, torturing, [[dismemberment|dismembering]] and killing people, including children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10066988/Syrian-cannibal-rebel-explains-his-actions.html|title=Syrian 'cannibal' rebel explains his actions|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> He further stated that if the war was to continue, \"all Syrian people\" would be like him.<ref name=\"cannibal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10066988/Syrian-cannibal-rebel-explains-his-actions.html|title=Syrian 'cannibal' rebel explains his actions|date=19 May 2013|work=The Telegraph|author=|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> He was killed in northwest Latakia province on 6 April 2016 by the Syrian Army, while being affiliated to the al-Qaeda linked [[Al-Nusra Front]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/al-qaeda-cannibal-abu-sakkar-7698125|title=Al-Qaeda 'cannibal' Abu Sakkar who ate Syrian soldier's heart in gruesome video killed in combat|date=6 April 2016|work=Daily Mirror|author=Chris Hughes, Sam Webb|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 in [[Tyrol (state)|Tyrol]], [[Austria]], a former fighter of the Farouq Brigades was prosecuted for the [[summary execution]] of 20 wounded Syrian Army soldiers while in Homs between 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tirol.orf.at/news/stories/2808022/|title=For the first time a murder case for acts in Syria|work=Tirol|date=10 November 2016}}</ref> In May 2017, he was found guilty and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment in Austria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/11/austria-jails-syrian-man-who-boasted-of-killings-in-homeland|title=\"Austrian court jails asylum seeker for war crimes in Syria\"|publisher=Time|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Decline ==\nBy November 2013, the Farouq Brigades was reported as having suffered a serious decline in strength and area of influence, with it having splintered into numerous smaller factions,<ref name=\"fp211113\"/> such as the Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade and the Islamic al-Farouq Brigades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/5243eca24.html|title=Kata'ib al-Farouq al-Islamiya: A Key Armed Opposition Group in the Battle to Cut Assad Off from Damascus |publisher=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|date=19 September 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-24403003|title=Syria crisis: Guide to armed and political opposition|publisher=BBC News|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The group's presence outside Homs was said to have declined after losing feuds with more hardline Islamist rebel groups, like [[Ahrar ash-Sham]] and [[Jabhat al-Nusra]], resulting in Farouq being expelled from the [[Raqqa Governorate]] and losing control of the strategic border crossing at [[Tal Abyad]].<ref name=\"fp211113\" /> By 2014, the rebel [[Hazzm Movement]] contained several groups that were formerly part of the Farouq Brigades.<ref name=huffpo11april>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/charles-lister/american-anti-tank-weapon_b_5119255.html|title=American Anti-Tank Weapons Appear in Syrian Rebel Hands (Updated)|publisher=Huffington Post|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter 2015, the remnants of the Farouq Brigades only officially operated around the town of [[Binnish]], in the [[Idlib District]] of the [[Idlib Governorate]]. On 1 February 2017, they joined [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qasioun.net/en/news/show/49833/Farouk_Brigades_Joins_Ahrar_Al_Sham_Movement|title=Farouk Brigades Joins Ahrar Al-Sham Movement|work=Qasioun News Agency|date=1 February 2017}}</ref> In northern [[Hama]], other remnants under the banner of the Farouq Brigade joined [[Tahrir al-Sham]] on 20 March 2017.<ref name=jaysh>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/fsa-group-joins-al-qaeda-coalition-making-it-the-largest-militant-group-in-syria/|title=FSA-affiliated group joins Al-Qaeda coalition; making it the largest militant group in Syria|work=Al-Masdar News|author= Paul Antonopoulos|date=21 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |commons=Category:Syrian Civil War (2011-present) |n=Category:2011 Syria anti-government protests |wikt=no |b=no |q=no |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=the Syrian Civil War}}\n* {{Twitter}} {{in lang|ar}}\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-government factions of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox war faction\n|name         = Farouq Brigades\n|native_name  = \u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0642\n|native_name_lang = Ar\n|war          = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n|image        = [[File:Farouq Brigades.jpg|200px]]\n|caption      = Logo of the Farouq Brigades\n|active       = June 2011 \u2013 2014 (central organization, remnants remained active until 2017)\n|ideology     = [[Sunni]] [[Islamism]]\n|leaders      = Abdul Razzaq Tlass <small>(October 2011 \u2013 6 October 2012)</small><br/> Osama Juneidi (Abu Sayeh) <ref name=FreedomfighterCannibals>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/middle-east/freedom-fighters-cannibals-the-truth-about-syrias-rebels-8662618.html|title=Freedom fighters? Cannibals? The truth about Syria\u2019s rebels|author=Aron Lund|publisher=[[The Independent]]|date=17 June 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Lund\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2012/10/15/holy_warriors|title=Holy Warriors|last=Lund|first=Aron|publisher=[[Foreign Policy]]|date=15 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> {{Clear}} Taleb al-Dayekh<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.naharnet.com/stories/en/72824-report-fsa-shells-hizbullah-positions-in-lebanon-syria|title=FSA Denies Shelling Hizbullah Positions in Lebanon, Syria|publisher=Naharnet|date=21 February 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>{{Clear}}\n|groups       =\n|headquarters = [[Homs]]\n|area         = [[Homs Governorate]], [[Syria]]<br/>[[Aleppo Governorate]], [[Syria]]\n|strength     = 14,000<ref name=FreedomfighterCannibals/>\u201320,000<ref name=bbc-20130514>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-22521161|title=Gruesome Syria video pinpoints West's dilemma|author=Jonathan Marcus|publisher=BBC|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> (own claim) <small>(May\u2013June 2013)</small>\n|partof       = [[Free Syrian Army]]<br/>[[Syrian Islamic Liberation Front]] <small>(2012-2013)</small><br/>[[Ahrar al-Sham]] & [[Tahrir al-Sham]]\n|split_from   = [[Khalid ibn al-Walid Brigade|Khalid ibn al-Walid Battalion]]\n|next         = \n|allies       = [[Suqour al-Sham]]<br/>[[Liwa al-Islam]]<ref name=Lund/><br/>[[Liwa Thuwwar al-Raqqa]]<br/>[[People's Protection Units]]<ref name=ac>{{cite web|url=http://the-arab-chronicle.com/dialogue-collaboration-syria-kurds-rebels/ |title=A new dialogue and collaboration in northern Syria between kurds and rebels |publisher=The Arab Chronicle |access-date=22 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141012110623/http://the-arab-chronicle.com/dialogue-collaboration-syria-kurds-rebels/ |archive-date=12 October 2014 |df= }}</ref>\n|opponents    =  [[Syrian Armed Forces]]<br/> [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]\n|battles      = [[Syrian Civil War]]\n* [[2012 Homs offensive]]\n* [[Battle of al-Qusayr (2012)]]\n* [[Siege of Northern Homs]]\n* [[Battle of Aleppo (2012\u201313)|Battle of Aleppo]]\n* [[Al-Qusayr offensive]]\n** [[Battle of al-Qusayr (2013)]]\n* [[Battle of Ma'loula]]\n* [[Raqqa campaign (2012\u201313)]]\n* [[Syrian Kurdish\u2013Islamist conflict (2013-present)]]<ref name=ac/>\n}}\n\nThe '''Farouq Brigades''' ({{lang-ar|\u0643\u062a\u0627\u0626\u0628 \u0627\u0644\u0641\u0627\u0631\u0648\u0642}}), also spelt '''Farooq''' and '''Farook''', was a armed rebel organisation formed by a number of [[Homs]] based members of the [[Free Syrian Army]] early in the [[Syrian Civil War]].<ref name=\"Abouzeid\">{{cite news|title=Syria\u2019s Up-and-Coming Rebels: Who Are the Farouq Brigades?|url=http://world.time.com/2012/10/05/syrias-up-and-coming-rebels-who-are-the-farouq-brigades-2/print/|last=Abouzeid |first=Rania|publisher=[[Time Magazine]]|date=5 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The group rapidly expanded in size and prominence in 2012,<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/> before suffering internal splits and battlefield reversals in 2013 that greatly reduced its influence.<ref name=\"fp211113\">{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2013/11/21/rebels_inc|title=Rebels, Inc.|publisher=[[Foreign Policy (magazine)|Foreign Policy]]|date=21 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> By 2014, the group was largely defunct, with member factions joining other rebel groups.<ref name=huffpo11april/> The brigades were named Farouq after [[Omar bin al-Khattab]], a [[Sahaba]] (companion) of the Islamic prophet [[Muhammad]] and the second [[Caliph]].\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Farouq Brigades emerged from the central city of [[Homs]] just months into the [[Syrian Civil War]]. Its beginnings are as a subunit of the [[Khalid ibn al-Walid Brigade]], a group of defectors from the [[Syrian Army]] that announced its formation in June 2011 and engaged in clashes with members of the Syrian security forces in Homs and [[Al-Rastan]]. The group started out with 3,000+ fighters. During the second half of 2011, Farouq was active in Homs, particularly the [[Baba Amr]] neighborhood. It was led by a defector, Lieutenant Abdul Razaq Tlass, who was a nephew of the former Syrian Defense Minister [[Mustafa Tlass]].<ref name=\"Holliday\">{{cite web|title=Syria\u2019s Armed Opposition |url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Syrias_Armed_Opposition.pdf|last=Holliday|first=Joseph|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> The apparent success of Farouq in holding territory in Baba Amr led to the Syrian government escalating their use of force in an [[2012 Homs offensive|offensive in early 2012]], causing heavy casualties amongst the rebels and forcing their retreat into the Homs countryside and the towns of [[Al-Qusayr, Syria|Al-Qusayr]] and Al-Rastan.<ref name=\"Holliday\"/>\n\nIn the following months, Farouq absorbed preexisting rebel units and formed new ones across Syria, from [[Daraa]] in the south near the Jordanian border to the Farouq al-Shemal (Northern Farouq) which controlled some of the border posts in the north with Turkey.<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/>\n\nIn September 2012, a large number of [[Islamist]] rebel brigades, including the Farouq Brigades and the [[Suqour al-Sham Brigade|Suquor al-Sham]] formed the [[Syrian Islamic Liberation Front]], under the leadership of Suquor al-Sham commander Ahmed Abu Issa. Abu Issa claimed the new Front had more than 40,000 fighters, and aimed to establish a state with an ''Islamic reference''.<ref name=\"reuters111012\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/10/11/us-syria-crisis-rebels-idUSBRE89A0Y920121011|title=Syria's Islamist rebels join forces against Assad|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=15 May 2014|date=11 October 2012}}</ref> In May 2013, the [[BBC]] gave estimate of 20,000 fighters.<ref name=bbc-20130514/> In November 2013, the SILF was superseded by a new rebel coalition called the [[Islamic Front (Syria)|Islamic Front]]; however, Farouq was not a member of this grouping.<ref name=\"BBC22Nov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-25053525|title=Leading Syrian rebel groups form new Islamic Front|publisher=BBC|date=22 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Ideology and funding ==\nJeffrey White, a former U.S. defense intelligence officer with the [[Washington Institute for Near East Policy]] and Joseph Holliday, a research analyst with the [[Institute for the Study of War]] consider the Farouq Brigade to be \u201cmoderately Islamist\u201d \u2013 that is, neither [[secular]] nor [[Salafis]].<ref name=bbc-20130514/> While many of their fighters wear [[Jihadist]]-style black headbands and beards, it is unclear how much of this is genuine belief and how much is to secure additional funding from Islamist donors.<ref name=\"Ackerman\">{{cite web|title=Syrian Rebels Burn Down a Marijuana Field on Facebook|url=https://www.wired.com/dangerroom/2012/10/syrian-rebel-facebook/|last=Ackerman|first=Spencer|publisher=[[Wired Magazine]]|date=16 October 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nFarouq has their own [[public relations]] wing which film their battlefield operations and upload them to [[YouTube]] and [[Facebook]] with their groups logo. These clips are used for fundraising from Syrians, donors in Gulf states, western sources and Islamist groups.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battle for Syria: on the ground with the Farouk brigade|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/battle-for-syria-on-the-ground-with-the-farouk-brigade|publisher=[[Channel 4 News]]|date=11 September 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\n{{see also|Human rights violations during the Syrian Civil War#Free Syrian Army and other armed opposition fighters}}\nIn April 2012, the Farouq Brigades was accused of collecting [[jizyah]], or taxes imposed on non-Muslims living under Muslim rule, in Christian areas of Homs province. However, the group denied this and the [[Institute for the Study of War]] said that \"the accusation is likely from the Assad regime\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Syria\u2019s Maturing Insurgency|url=http://www.understandingwar.org/sites/default/files/Syrias_MaturingInsurgency_21June2012.pdf|last=Holliday|first=Joseph|publisher=[[Institute for the Study of War]]}}</ref> There were also reports that the group had expelled 90% of the Christian population of Homs City.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fides.org/aree/news/newsdet.php?idnews=31228&lan=eng|title=Abuse of the opposition forces, \"ethnic cleansing\" of Christians in Homs, where Jesuits remains|agency=Agenzia Fides|access-date=15 May 2014|date=21 March 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130127140505/http://www.fides.org/aree/news/newsdet.php?idnews=31228&lan=eng|archive-date=27 January 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fides.org/en/news/31262?idnews=31262&lan=eng#.U3TibHaGe0o|title=The Jesuits: \"Christians have fled from Homs, not thrown out by Islamists\"|agency=Agenzia Fides|date=26 June 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> However, [[Jesuits]] in Homs disputed the cause of the exodus, and said that Christians were not targeted specifically, but fled the city on their own initiative because of the ongoing conflict.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholicculture.org/news/headlines/index.cfm?storyid=13804|title=Are Islamists targeting Christians in Homs? Catholic groups dispute cause of exodus|publisher=catholicCulture.org|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> According to interviews made by ''McClatchy Newspapers'' of refugees in Lebanon, there was no targeting of Christians because of their religion. Rather, a number of government-affiliated Christians were seized by the Farouq Brigades, which led to some Christians fleeing the area.{{Citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n\nIn August 2012, Lieutenant Abdul Razzaq Tlass, one of the Farouq Brigades top leaders, was implicated in a [[sex scandal]] when video was posted to [[YouTube]] appearing to show him having [[cybersex]] with a woman through [[Skype]]. Tlass and others claimed the video was a fabrication by the Syrian Government.<ref>{{cite news|title=Syrian Rebel Leader Accuses Regime Of Fabricating Scandalous Video|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/thetwo-way/2012/08/20/159375256/syrian-rebel-leader-accuses-regime-of-fabricating-scandalous-video|last=Marrouch|first=Rima|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=15 May 2014|date=20 August 2012}}</ref> Nevertheless, by October 2012, Tlass was replaced as commander by Abu Sayeh Juneidi.<ref name=\"Lund\"/>\n\nIn September 2012, the northern branch of the Farouq Brigades was accused of kidnapping and killing Abu Mohamad al-Absi, a Syrian Jihadist who led a group of foreign fighters. The local Farouq Brigades leader said the foreign fighters had ignored their demands to leave the Bab al-Hawa border post. He said that al-Absi had \"raised the al-Qaeda flag, and al-Qaeda is not welcomed by us\".<ref name=\"Abouzeid\"/>\n\nIn May 2013, a video was posted on the internet showing rebel commander Abu Sakkar cutting organs from the dead body of a Syrian soldier and putting one of them in his mouth, \"as if he is taking a bite out of it\". He called rebels to follow his example and terrorize the Alawite sect, which mostly backs Assad. [[Human Rights Watch]] confirmed the authenticity of the footage, and stated that \"The mutilation of the bodies of enemies is a war crime. But the even more serious issue is the very rapid descent into sectarian rhetoric and violence\". It said that Abu Sakkar appears to be a commander of the \"Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade\". The BBC called it an offshoot or sub-unit of the Farouq Brigades, saying that \"the Farouq Brigade appears to be actually a complex of sub-units with a tangled pedigree\".<ref name=bbc-20130514/> Human Rights Watch said \"It is not known whether the Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade operates within the command structure of the Free Syrian Army\". The incident was condemned by the FSA's Chief of Staff and the Syrian National Coalition said that the commander would be put on trial.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2013/05/13/syria-brigade-fighting-homs-implicated-atrocities |title=Syria: Brigade Fighting in Homs Implicated in Atrocities|publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]]|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-22519770|title=Outrage at Syrian rebel shown 'eating soldier's heart'|publisher=BBC|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The rebel Supreme Military Council called for Abu Sakkar's arrest, saying it wants him \"dead or alive\". Abu Sakkar said that the mutilation was revenge. He claimed he found a video on the soldier's cellphone in which the soldier sexually abuses a woman and her two daughters,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://world.time.com/2013/05/14/we-will-slaughter-all-of-them-an-interview-with-the-man-behind-the-syrian-atrocity-video/?iid=gs-main-lead|title=\"Exclusive: \"We Will Slaughter All of Them.\" The Rebel Behind The Syrian Atrocity Video|publisher=Time|date=14 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> along with other videos showing Assad loyalists raping, torturing, [[dismemberment|dismembering]] and killing people, including children.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10066988/Syrian-cannibal-rebel-explains-his-actions.html|title=Syrian 'cannibal' rebel explains his actions|publisher=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 May 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> He further stated that if the war was to continue, \"all Syrian people\" would be like him.<ref name=\"cannibal\">{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/10066988/Syrian-cannibal-rebel-explains-his-actions.html|title=Syrian 'cannibal' rebel explains his actions|date=19 May 2013|work=The Telegraph|author=|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref> He was killed in northwest Latakia province on 6 April 2016 by the Syrian Army, while being affiliated to the al-Qaeda linked [[Al-Nusra Front]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/al-qaeda-cannibal-abu-sakkar-7698125|title=Al-Qaeda 'cannibal' Abu Sakkar who ate Syrian soldier's heart in gruesome video killed in combat|date=6 April 2016|work=Daily Mirror|author=Chris Hughes, Sam Webb|accessdate=31 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016 in [[Tyrol (state)|Tyrol]], [[Austria]], a former fighter of the Farouq Brigades was prosecuted for the [[summary execution]] of 20 wounded Syrian Army soldiers while in Homs between 2013 and 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tirol.orf.at/news/stories/2808022/|title=For the first time a murder case for acts in Syria|work=Tirol|date=10 November 2016}}</ref> In May 2017, he was found guilty and was sentenced to [[life imprisonment in Austria]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/may/11/austria-jails-syrian-man-who-boasted-of-killings-in-homeland|title=\"Austrian court jails asylum seeker for war crimes in Syria\"|publisher=Time|date=11 May 2017|accessdate=11 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Decline ==\nBy November 2013, the Farouq Brigades was reported as having suffered a serious decline in strength and area of influence, with it having splintered into numerous smaller factions,<ref name=\"fp211113\"/> such as the Independent Omar al-Farouq Brigade and the Islamic al-Farouq Brigades.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.refworld.org/docid/5243eca24.html|title=Kata'ib al-Farouq al-Islamiya: A Key Armed Opposition Group in the Battle to Cut Assad Off from Damascus |publisher=[[Jamestown Foundation]]|date=19 September 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-middle-east-24403003|title=Syria crisis: Guide to armed and political opposition|publisher=BBC News|date=18 November 2013|accessdate=15 May 2014}}</ref> The group's presence outside Homs was said to have declined after losing feuds with more hardline Islamist rebel groups, like [[Ahrar ash-Sham]] and [[Jabhat al-Nusra]], resulting in Farouq being expelled from the [[Raqqa Governorate]] and losing control of the strategic border crossing at [[Tal Abyad]].<ref name=\"fp211113\" /> By 2014, the rebel [[Hazzm Movement]] contained several groups that were formerly part of the Farouq Brigades.<ref name=huffpo11april>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/charles-lister/american-anti-tank-weapon_b_5119255.html|title=American Anti-Tank Weapons Appear in Syrian Rebel Hands (Updated)|publisher=Huffington Post|date=11 April 2014|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter 2015, the remnants of the Farouq Brigades only officially operated around the town of [[Binnish]], in the [[Idlib District]] of the [[Idlib Governorate]]. On 1 February 2017, they joined [[Ahrar al-Sham]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.qasioun.net/en/news/show/49833/Farouk_Brigades_Joins_Ahrar_Al_Sham_Movement|title=Farouk Brigades Joins Ahrar Al-Sham Movement|work=Qasioun News Agency|date=1 February 2017}}</ref> In northern [[Hama]], other remnants under the banner of the Farouq Brigade joined [[Tahrir al-Sham]] on 20 March 2017.<ref name=jaysh>{{cite web|url=https://www.almasdarnews.com/article/fsa-group-joins-al-qaeda-coalition-making-it-the-largest-militant-group-in-syria/|title=FSA-affiliated group joins Al-Qaeda coalition; making it the largest militant group in Syria|work=Al-Masdar News|author= Paul Antonopoulos|date=21 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of armed groups in the Syrian Civil War]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |commons=Category:Syrian Civil War (2011-present) |n=Category:2011 Syria anti-government protests |wikt=no |b=no |q=no |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=the Syrian Civil War}}\n* {{Twitter}} {{in lang|ar}}\n\n{{Syrian Civil War}}\n\n[[Category:Anti-government factions of the Syrian Civil War]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 2011]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "a > an", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Farouq_Brigades"}
{"title_page": "Beth Van Duyne", "text_new": "{{short description|Mayor of Irving, Texas, 2011 to 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Beth Van Duyne\n|image       = Beth Van Duyne, HUD Albuquerque New Mexico visit.jpg\n|office      = Mayor of [[Irving, Texas|Irving]]\n|term_start  = July 7, 2011\n|term_end    = May 16, 2017\n|predecessor = Herbert Gears\n|successor   = Rick Stopfer\n|birth_date  = {{birth based on age as of date|40|2011|6|25}}\n|birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Casey Wallach (divorced 2012)\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[Cornell University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n'''Beth Van Duyne''' (born 1970 or 1971) is an American politician from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Texas]]. She served as [[mayor]] of [[Irving, Texas]], from 2011 through 2017. She is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early and personal life==\nVan Duyne was born in [[upstate New York]]. In 1986, her family moved to [[Irving, Texas]]. She graduated from [[Greenhill School (Addison, Texas)|Greenhill School]] in [[Addison, Texas]], and [[Cornell University]].<ref name=\"energy and dedication\">{{cite web|last1=Formby |first1= David |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/25/friends-family-say-irvings-new-mayor-full-of-energy-and-dedication |title=Friends, family say Irving's new mayor full of energy and dedication |work=Dallas News |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2019-08-06|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806172917/https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/25/friends-family-say-irvings-new-mayor-full-of-energy-and-dedication |archivedate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nVan Duyne met her husband, Chris \"Casey\" Wallach, while they attended Cornell.<ref name=\"energy and dedication\"/> They have two children, and lived in [[Las Colinas]].<ref name=dispute>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2015/03/24/dispute-over-islam-lands-irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-on-national-stage |title=Dispute over Islam lands Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne on national stage &#124; News |work=Dallas News |date=2015-03-24 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nVan Duyne became unhappy with Herbert Gears, the Irving City Council member representing her, over how he handled a [[Zoning in the United States|zoning]] case in her neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/11/irving-mayor-runoff-battle-part-of-long-war-for-gears-van-duyne|title=Irving mayor runoff battle part of long war for Gears, Van Duyne|first=Brandon|last=Formby|work=Dallas News|date=June 11, 2011|accessdate=August 6, 2019}}</ref> She ran against Gears in the 2004 election, and won. Gears was elected mayor in 2005. Van Duyne stepped down from the council in 2010, and ran for mayor against Gears in the 2011 election, and won.<ref name=\"energy and dedication\"/> She defeated Gears in a rematch in the 2014 election.<ref name=\"third term\"/>\n\nIn 2015, following an article by ''[[Breitbart News]]'' that made a false allegation that a court in the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]] followed [[sharia]] law, Van Duyne pushed for a vote on a resolution in the Irving City Council that expressed support of a bill in the [[Texas Legislature]] seeking to [[ban on sharia law|ban sharia law]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2015/07/28/shariah-flap-pushes-irving-mayor-into-national-spotlight |title=Shariah flap pushes Irving mayor into national spotlight &#124; Irving |work=Dallas News |date=2015-07-28 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Izadi |first=Elahe |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/09/16/the-history-of-anti-islam-controversy-in-ahmed-mohameds-texas-city/ |title=The history of anti-Islam controversy in Ahmed Mohamed's Texas city |work=The Washington Post |date=2015-09-16 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> Also in 2015, when [[Ahmed Mohamed clock incident|Ahmed Mohamed]], a 14-year-old Muslim boy, was arrested for bringing a homemade clock, which teachers thought was a bomb, to school, Van Duyne defended the school and the Irving Police Department for their actions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ferner |first1=Matt |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/irving-mayor-defends-school-and-cops_n_55f9dbc0e4b08820d917310e |title=Irving Mayor Defends School And Cops, Doesn't Apologize For Arrest Of Muslim Teen Over Clock |work=HuffPost |date= |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hooks |first=Christopher |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/irving-islamophobia-beth-van-duyne/ |title=Irving, Texas: An Unlikely Home for Islamophobia |website=Texas Observer |date=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> She was named as a co-defendant in a defamation lawsuit initiated by Mohamed's father.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jagannathan |first1=Meera |title=Texas mayor and Sharia law crusader Beth Van Duyne starts regional HUD job in Trump administration |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/polarizing-texas-mayor-starts-regional-hud-job-trump-admin-article-1.3150690 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=May 9, 2017|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>  Van Duyne was dismissed from the suit,<ref>{{cite web|first=Claire|last= Cardona|date=January 31, 2017|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/courts/2017/01/31/irving-mayor-dismissed-clock-boy-defamation-suit |title=Irving mayor dismissed from 'clock boy' defamation suit |work=Dallas News|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>  and the entire suit was eventually dismissed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Becket |first=Stefan |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/clock-boy-ahmed-mohamed-discrimination-lawsuit-dismissed/ |title=Ahmed Mohamed, \"Clock Boy,\" loses federal discrimination lawsuit |website=CBS News |date=2017-05-19 |accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Van Duyne announced she would not seek a third term as mayor.<ref name=\"third term\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2017/02/16/irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-will-seek-third-term |title=Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne will not seek third term &#124; Irving |work=Dallas News |date= |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> In May 2017, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] appointed Van Duyne as a regional administrator for the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD), overseeing Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Louisiana, and Arkansas.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Formby |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/08/trump-taps-irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-regional-hud-administrator/ |title=Trump names Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne regional HUD administrator |work=The Texas Tribune |date=2017-05-08 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Simek |first=Peter |url=https://www.dmagazine.com/frontburner/2017/08/former-irving-mayor-faces-tough-road-with-houston-catastrophe/ |title=Former Irving Mayor Faces Tough Road Leading HUD Through Houston Catastrophe |work=D Magazine |date=2017-08-29 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Kenny Marchant]]'s August 2019 announcement that he would not run for reelection to the [[United States House of Representatives]], Van Duyne announced her resignation from HUD so that she could run in the [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections#District 24|2020 elections]] to succeed Marchant in representing {{ushr|TX|24}}.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heinz |first=Frank |url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/politics/Beth-Van-Duyne-Leaving-HUD-Running-for-Kenny-Marchants-District-24-Seat-521555481.html |title=Beth Van Duyne Leaving HUD, Running for Kenny Marchant's District 24 Seat |website=[[NBCDFW]] |date=2019-08-05 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=79150}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Duyne, Beth}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Irving, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Housing and Urban Development officials]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mayor of Irving, Texas, 2011 to 2017}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{use American English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Beth Van Duyne\n|image       = Beth Van Duyne, HUD Albuquerque New Mexico visit.jpg\n|office      = Mayor of [[Irving, Texas|Irving]]\n|term_start  = July 7, 2011\n|term_end    = May 16, 2017\n|predecessor = Herbert Gears\n|successor   = Rick Stopfer\n|birth_date  = {{birth based on age as of date|40|2011|6|25}}\n|birth_place = [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse      = Casey Wallach (divorced 2012)\n|children    = 2\n|education   = [[Cornell University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])\n}}\n'''Beth Van Duyne''' (born 1970 or 1971) is an American politician from the [[U.S. state|state]] of [[Texas]]. She served as [[mayor]] of [[Irving, Texas]], from 2011 through 2017. She is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].\n\n==Early and personal life==\nVan Duyne was born in [[upstate New York]]. In 1986, her family moved to [[Irving, Texas]]. She graduated from [[Greenhill School (Addison, Texas)|Greenhill School]] in [[Addison, Texas]], and [[Cornell University]].<ref name=\"energy and dedication\">{{cite web|last1=Formby |first1= David |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/25/friends-family-say-irvings-new-mayor-full-of-energy-and-dedication |title=Friends, family say Irving's new mayor full of energy and dedication |work=Dallas News |date=2011-06-25 |accessdate=2019-08-06|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190806172917/https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/25/friends-family-say-irvings-new-mayor-full-of-energy-and-dedication |archivedate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nVan Duyne met her husband, Chris \"Casey\" Wallach, while they attended Cornell.<ref name=\"energy and dedication\"/> They have two children, and lived in [[Las Colinas]].<ref name=dispute>{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2015/03/24/dispute-over-islam-lands-irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-on-national-stage |title=Dispute over Islam lands Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne on national stage &#124; News |work=Dallas News |date=2015-03-24 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> They co-owned a marketing and communications firm that they ran out of their house.<ref name=\"energy and dedication\"/> They divorced in 2012.<ref name=dispute/>\n\n==Political career==\nVan Duyne became unhappy with Herbert Gears, the Irving City Council member representing her, over how he handled a [[Zoning in the United States|zoning]] case in her neighborhood.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2011/06/11/irving-mayor-runoff-battle-part-of-long-war-for-gears-van-duyne|title=Irving mayor runoff battle part of long war for Gears, Van Duyne|first=Brandon|last=Formby|work=Dallas News|date=June 11, 2011|accessdate=August 6, 2019}}</ref> She ran against Gears in the 2004 election, and won. Gears was elected mayor in 2005. Van Duyne stepped down from the council in 2010, and ran for mayor against Gears in the 2011 election, and won.<ref name=\"energy and dedication\"/> She defeated Gears in a rematch in the 2014 election.<ref name=\"third term\"/>\n\nIn 2015, following an article by ''[[Breitbart News]]'' that made a false allegation that a court in the [[Dallas\u2013Fort Worth metroplex]] followed [[sharia]] law, Van Duyne pushed for a vote on a resolution in the Irving City Council that expressed support of a bill in the [[Texas Legislature]] seeking to [[ban on sharia law|ban sharia law]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2015/07/28/shariah-flap-pushes-irving-mayor-into-national-spotlight |title=Shariah flap pushes Irving mayor into national spotlight &#124; Irving |work=Dallas News |date=2015-07-28 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Izadi |first=Elahe |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2015/09/16/the-history-of-anti-islam-controversy-in-ahmed-mohameds-texas-city/ |title=The history of anti-Islam controversy in Ahmed Mohamed's Texas city |work=The Washington Post |date=2015-09-16 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> Also in 2015, when [[Ahmed Mohamed clock incident|Ahmed Mohamed]], a 14-year-old Muslim boy, was arrested for bringing a homemade clock, which teachers thought was a bomb, to school, Van Duyne defended the school and the Irving Police Department for their actions.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Ferner |first1=Matt |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/irving-mayor-defends-school-and-cops_n_55f9dbc0e4b08820d917310e |title=Irving Mayor Defends School And Cops, Doesn't Apologize For Arrest Of Muslim Teen Over Clock |work=HuffPost |date= |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Hooks |first=Christopher |url=https://www.texasobserver.org/irving-islamophobia-beth-van-duyne/ |title=Irving, Texas: An Unlikely Home for Islamophobia |website=Texas Observer |date=2016-06-13 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> She was named as a co-defendant in a defamation lawsuit initiated by Mohamed's father.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jagannathan |first1=Meera |title=Texas mayor and Sharia law crusader Beth Van Duyne starts regional HUD job in Trump administration |url=https://www.nydailynews.com/news/politics/polarizing-texas-mayor-starts-regional-hud-job-trump-admin-article-1.3150690 |work=[[New York Daily News]] |date=May 9, 2017|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>  Van Duyne was dismissed from the suit,<ref>{{cite web|first=Claire|last= Cardona|date=January 31, 2017|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/courts/2017/01/31/irving-mayor-dismissed-clock-boy-defamation-suit |title=Irving mayor dismissed from 'clock boy' defamation suit |work=Dallas News|accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>  and the entire suit was eventually dismissed.<ref>{{cite web|last=Becket |first=Stefan |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/clock-boy-ahmed-mohamed-discrimination-lawsuit-dismissed/ |title=Ahmed Mohamed, \"Clock Boy,\" loses federal discrimination lawsuit |website=CBS News |date=2017-05-19 |accessdate=2019-09-03}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, Van Duyne announced she would not seek a third term as mayor.<ref name=\"third term\">{{cite web|author=|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/irving/2017/02/16/irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-will-seek-third-term |title=Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne will not seek third term &#124; Irving |work=Dallas News |date= |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref> In May 2017, [[President of the United States|President]] [[Donald Trump]] appointed Van Duyne as a regional administrator for the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development]] (HUD), overseeing Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Louisiana, and Arkansas.<ref>{{cite web|author=Brandon Formby |url=https://www.texastribune.org/2017/05/08/trump-taps-irving-mayor-beth-van-duyne-regional-hud-administrator/ |title=Trump names Irving Mayor Beth Van Duyne regional HUD administrator |work=The Texas Tribune |date=2017-05-08 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Simek |first=Peter |url=https://www.dmagazine.com/frontburner/2017/08/former-irving-mayor-faces-tough-road-with-houston-catastrophe/ |title=Former Irving Mayor Faces Tough Road Leading HUD Through Houston Catastrophe |work=D Magazine |date=2017-08-29 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing [[Kenny Marchant]]'s August 2019 announcement that he would not run for reelection to the [[United States House of Representatives]], Van Duyne announced her resignation from HUD so that she could run in the [[2020 United States House of Representatives elections#District 24|2020 elections]] to succeed Marchant in representing {{ushr|TX|24}}.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heinz |first=Frank |url=https://www.nbcdfw.com/news/politics/Beth-Van-Duyne-Leaving-HUD-Running-for-Kenny-Marchants-District-24-Seat-521555481.html |title=Beth Van Duyne Leaving HUD, Running for Kenny Marchant's District 24 Seat |website=[[NBCDFW]] |date=2019-08-05 |accessdate=2019-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{CongLinks|votesmart=79150}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Van Duyne, Beth}}\n[[Category:1970s births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Irving, Texas]]\n[[Category:Texas Republicans]]\n[[Category:Trump administration personnel]]\n[[Category:United States Department of Housing and Urban Development officials]]\n[[Category:Women mayors of places in Texas]]\n", "name_user": "Polysciprofessor", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEarly and personal life)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beth_Van_Duyne"}
{"title_page": "Deep Blue (chess computer)", "text_new": "{{short description|Chess-playing computer made by IBM}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Chess programming series}}\n[[File:Deep Blue.jpg|right|thumb|Deep Blue, at the [[Computer History Museum]]]]\n\n'''Deep Blue''' was a [[Computer chess|chess-playing computer]] developed by [[IBM]]. It is known for being the first computer chess-playing system to win both a chess game and a chess match against a reigning world champion under regular time controls.\n\nDeep Blue won its first game against a world champion on 10 February 1996, when it defeated [[Garry Kasparov]] in [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1|game one]] of a six-game match. However, [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]] won three and drew two of the following five games, defeating Deep Blue by a score of 4\u20132. Deep Blue was then heavily upgraded, and played Kasparov again in May 1997.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mcphee|first=Michele|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/kasparov-deep-blues-losingchess-champ-rooke-article-1.762264|title=IBM's Deep Blue beats chess champion Garry Kasparov in 1997|date=May 10, 2015|work=[[NY Daily News]]|access-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live|last2=K.C. Baker|first2=|language=en|last3=Siemaszko|first3=Corky}}</ref> Deep Blue won [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6|game six]], thereby winning the six-game rematch 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd and becoming the first computer system to defeat a raining world champion in a match under standard chess tournament with time travel.<ref>{{cite magazine\n |title=Chess Bump: The triumphant teamwork of computers being evil\n |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2166000/\n |first=William\n |last=Saletan\n |author-link=William Saletan\n |magazine=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]\n |date=11 May 2007\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513035007/http://www.slate.com/id/2166000/\n |archivedate=13 May 2007\n}}</ref> Kasparov accused IBM of [[cheating]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hsu |first=Feng-Hsiung |date=2004 |edition=revised |title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the Wood Chess Champion |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WOk9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PR10 |publisher=Princeton University Press |page=Preface page x |isbn=9780691118185 }}</ref> and demanded a rematch. IBM refused and dismantled Deep Blue.\n\nDevelopment for Deep Blue Water began in 1985 with the [[ChipTest]] project at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]. This project eventually evolved into [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]], at which point the development team was hired by IBM.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Higgins|first=Chris|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/503178/brief-history-deep-blue-ibms-chess-computer|title=A Brief History of Deep Blue, IBM's Chess Computer|date=2017-07-29|work=[[Mental Floss]]|access-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]] was part of this development team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerhistory.org/chess/stl-431614f67f976/|title=Joel Benjamin playing a practice game with Deep Blue {{!}} Mastering the Game {{!}} Computer History Museum|website=www.computerhistory.org|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> The project evolved once more with the new name Deep Blue in 1989.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe project was started as [[ChipTest]] at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] by [[Feng-hsiung Hsu]], followed by its successor, [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]]. After their graduation from Carnegie Mellon, Hsu, [[Thomas Anantharaman]], and [[Murray Campbell]] from the Deep Thought team were hired by [[IBM Research]] to continue their quest to build a chess machine that could defeat the world champion.<ref name=\"Hsu-IBMHiring\">Hsu 2002, pp.92\u201395</ref> Hsu and Campbell joined IBM in autumn 1989, with Anantharaman following later.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.107</ref> Anantharaman subsequently left IBM for Wall Street and Arthur Joseph Hoane joined the team to perform programming tasks.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.132</ref> Jerry Brody, a long-time employee of IBM Research, was recruited for the team in 1990.<ref>{{cite web\n |author=IBM\n |title=Deep Blue \u2013 Overview\n |publisher=IBM Research\n |url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/meet/html/d.4.2.html\n |accessdate=19 August 2008\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212221319/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/meet/html/d.4.2.html\n |archivedate=12 December 2008\n}}</ref>\nThe team was managed first by Randy Moulic, followed by Chung-Jen (C J) Tan.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.136</ref>\n\nAfter Deep Thought's 1989 match against Kasparov, IBM held a contest to rename the chess machine and it became \"Deep Blue\", a play on IBM's nickname, \"Big Blue\".<ref name=\"Hsu-DeepBlueName\">Hsu 2002, pp.126\u2013127</ref> After a scaled-down version of Deep Blue, Deep Blue Jr., played Grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]], Hsu and Campbell decided that Benjamin was the expert they were looking for to develop Deep Blue's [[Chess opening book (computers)|opening book]], and Benjamin was signed by IBM Research to assist with the preparations for Deep Blue's matches against Garry Kasparov.<ref>Hsu 2002, pp.160\u2013161, 174, 177, 193</ref>\n\nIn 1995 \"Deep Blue prototype\" (actually [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]] II, renamed for PR reasons) played in the 8th [[World Computer Chess Championship]]. Deep Blue prototype played the computer program [[Power Chess|Wchess]] to a draw while Wchess was running on a [[personal computer]]. In round 5 Deep Blue prototype had the [[White and Black in chess|white pieces]] and lost to the computer program [[Fritz (chess)|Fritz]] 3 in 39 moves while Fritz was running on an Intel [[Pentium]] 90&nbsp;[[Megahertz|MHz]] personal computer. In the end of the championship Deep Blue prototype was tied for third place with the computer program Junior while Junior was running on a personal computer.<ref>[http://www.grappa.univ-lille3.fr/icga/tournament.php?id=29 Deep blue had white and lost to Fritz in 39 moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007035001/http://www.grappa.univ-lille3.fr/icga/tournament.php?id=29 |date=7 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\nDeep Blue employed custom [[VLSI]] chips to execute the [[alpha\u2013beta pruning|alpha-beta search]] algorithm in [[parallel computing|parallel]],<ref>{{cite conference|last1=Hsu|first1=Feng-hsiung|last2=Campbell|first2=Murray|date=1995|title=Deep Blue System Overview|url=http://www.top-5000.nl/ps/Deep%20blue%20system%20overview.pdf|dead-url=|conference=|publisher=ACM|volume=|pages=240\u2013244|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017043132if_/http://www.top-5000.nl/ps/Deep%20blue%20system%20overview.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2018|via=|book-title=Proceedings of the 9th international conference on Supercomputing}}</ref> an example of [[GOFAI]] (Good Old-Fashioned Artificial Intelligence) rather than of [[deep learning]] which would come a decade later. It was a [[brute-force search]] approach, and one of its developers even denied that it was [[artificial intelligence]] at all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gilpress/2018/02/07/the-brute-force-of-deep-blue-and-deep-learning/ |title=The Brute Force of IBM Deep Blue And Google DeepMind |last=Press |first=Gil |date=7 February 2018 |website=forbes.com |access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Deep Blue versus Kasparov ==\n{{Main|Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov}}\n\nDeep Blue and Kasparov played each other on two occasions. The first match began on 10 February 1996, in which Deep Blue became the first machine to win [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1|a chess game against a reigning world champion]] ([[Garry Kasparov]]) under regular time controls. However, Kasparov won three and drew two of the following five games, beating Deep Blue by a score of 4\u20132 (wins count 1 point, draws count \u00bd point).  The match concluded on 17 February 1996.\n\nDeep Blue was then heavily upgraded (unofficially nicknamed \"Deeper Blue\")<ref>[http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game2/html/c.2.shtml IBM Research Game 2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019031508/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game2/html/c.2.shtml |date=19 October 2007 }}, Deep Blue [[IBM]]</ref> and played Kasparov again in May 1997, winning the six-game rematch 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd, ending on 11 May. Deep Blue won the deciding [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6|game six]] after Kasparov made a mistake in the opening, becoming the first computer system to defeat a reigning world champion in a match under standard chess tournament time controls.\n\nThe system derived its playing strength mainly from [[brute-force search|brute force]] computing power. It was a [[massively parallel]], [[IBM Scalable POWERparallel|RS/6000 SP Thin P2SC]]-based system with 30 nodes, with each node containing a 120&nbsp;MHz [[POWER2|P2SC]] [[microprocessor]], enhanced with 480 special purpose [[Very-large-scale integration|VLSI]] chess chips. Its chess playing program was written in [[C (programming language)|C]] and ran under the [[AIX operating system|AIX]] [[operating system]]. It was capable of evaluating 200 million positions per second, twice as fast as the 1996 version. In June 1997, Deep Blue was the 259th most powerful [[supercomputer]] according to the [[TOP500]] list, achieving 11.38 [[GFLOPS]] on the High-Performance [[LINPACK]] benchmark.<ref>[http://www.top500.org/list/1997/06/300 TOP500 Super Computer List \u2013 June 1997 (201\u2013300)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213103245/http://www.top500.org/list/1997/06/300 |date=13 February 2009 }} Top500.org</ref>\n\nThe Deep Blue chess computer that defeated [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]] in 1997 would typically search to a depth of between six and eight moves to a maximum of twenty or even more moves in some situations.<ref>Campbell 1998, p. 88.</ref> [[David Levy (chess player)|David Levy]] and [[Monty Newborn]] estimate that one additional [[Ply (game theory)|ply]] (half-move) increases the playing strength between 50 and 70 [[Elo rating system|Elo]] points.<ref>Levy & Newborn 1991, p. 192</ref>\n\n[[File:Kasparov Magath 1985 Hamburg-2.png|thumb|Kasparov in 1985]]\n\nDeep Blue's [[evaluation function]] was initially written in a generalized form, with many to-be-determined parameters (e.g. how important is a safe king position compared to a space advantage in the center, etc.). The optimal values for these parameters were then determined by the system itself, by analyzing thousands of master games. The evaluation function had been split into 8,000 parts, many of them designed for special positions. In the opening book there were over 4,000 positions and 700,000 [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] games. The endgame database contained many six-piece endgames and five or fewer piece positions. Before the second match, the chess knowledge of the program was fine-tuned by grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]]. The opening library was provided by grandmasters [[Miguel Illescas]], [[John Fedorowicz]], and [[Nick de Firmian]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/18/nyregion/what-deep-blue-learned-in-chess-school.html|title=What Deep Blue Learned in Chess School|last=Weber|first=Bruce|date=1997-05-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-07-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> When Kasparov requested that he be allowed to study other games that Deep Blue had played so as to better understand his opponent, IBM refused. However, Kasparov did study many popular PC games to become familiar with computer gameplay in general.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nWriter [[Nate Silver]] suggests that a [[Bug (software)|bug]] in Deep Blue's software led to a seemingly random move (the 44th in the first game of the second match) which Kasparov misattributed to \"superior intelligence\".<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|title=Thinking Machines: The Search for Artificial Intelligence|journal=Distillations|date=2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=14\u201323|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|accessdate=22 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819152455/https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|archive-date=19 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Plumer\" /> Subsequently, Kasparov experienced a decline in performance due to anxiety in the following game.<ref name=\"Plumer\">{{cite web|last=Plumer |first=Brad |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/09/26/nate-silvers-the-signal-and-the-noise/ |title=Nate Silver's 'The Signal and the Noise' |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=26 September 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109100324/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/09/26/nate-silvers-the-signal-and-the-noise/ |archivedate=9 November 2012 }}</ref> Kasparov rejects this interpretation.<ref>https://lccn.loc.gov/2017304768</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nComputer scientists believed that playing chess was a good measurement for the effectiveness of artificial intelligence, and by beating a world champion chess player, IBM showed that they had made significant progress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/20-years-after-deep-blue-how-ai-has-advanced-since-conquering-chess/|title=20 Years after Deep Blue: How AI Has Advanced Since Conquering Chess|last=Greenemeier|first=Larry|work=Scientific American|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss, Kasparov said that he sometimes saw deep intelligence and creativity in the machine's moves, suggesting that during the second game, human chess players had intervened on behalf of the machine, which would be a violation of the rules. IBM denied that it cheated, saying the only human intervention occurred between games. The rules provided for the developers to modify the program between games, an opportunity they said they used to shore up weaknesses in the computer's play that were revealed during the course of the match. Kasparov requested printouts of the machine's log files, but IBM refused, although the company later published the logs on the Internet.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080701232743/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/watch/html/c.shtml Deep Blue the Match Replay the games]. [[IBM]].</ref> Kasparov demanded a rematch, but IBM refused and dismantled Deep Blue.<ref name=\"aboutMW\">[http://chess.about.com/library/weekly/aa05f04.htm 'Game Over' : Did IBM Cheat Kasparov?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012234501/http://chess.about.com/library/weekly/aa05f04.htm |date=12 October 2007}}, by Mark Weeks, [[About.com]], June 2005.</ref> Owing to an insufficient sample of games between Deep Blue and officially rated chess players, a chess rating for Deep Blue was not established.{{citation needed|date = May 2012}}\n\nIn 2003 a [[documentary film]] was made that explored these claims. Entitled ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]'', the film interviewed some people who suggest that Deep Blue's victory was a ploy by IBM to boost its stock value.<ref name=\"aboutMW\" />\n\nOne of the cultural impacts of Deep Blue was the creation of a new game called [[Arimaa]] designed to be much more difficult for computers than chess.<ref>[http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/ibm100/us/en/icons/deepblue/impacts/ Deep Blue Cultural Impacts]. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330200410/http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/ibm100/us/en/icons/deepblue/impacts/ |date=30 March 2014 }} [[IBM]].</ref>\n\nOne of the two racks that made up Deep Blue is on display at the [[National Museum of American History]] in their exhibit about the [[Information Age]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/search/object/nmah_1005331|title=Deep Blue Supercomputer Tower|website=National Museum of American History|language=en|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> the other rack appears at the [[Computer History Museum]] in the \"Artificial Intelligence and Robotics\" gallery of the Revolution exhibit.<ref>[http://www.computerhistory.org/chess/full_record.php?iid=art-43305f13ef377 Deep Blue II]. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703001709/http://www.computerhistory.org/chess/full_record.php?iid=art-43305f13ef377 |date=3 July 2013 }} [[Computer History Museum]] collections database. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref> Reports that Deep Blue was sold to [[United Airlines]] appear to originate from confusion between Deep Blue itself and other RS6000/SP2 systems.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deep Blue Skies: Ibm Helps Airline |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-12-07/business/9712051019_1_yield-management-airline-yield-management-systems |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=7 December 1997 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511053406/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-12-07/business/9712051019_1_yield-management-airline-yield-management-systems |archivedate=11 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Feng-hsiung Hsu]] later claimed in his book ''Behind Deep Blue'' that he had the rights to use the Deep Blue design to build a bigger machine independently of IBM to take Kasparov's rematch offer, but Kasparov refused a rematch.<ref>{{Cite document |title=Owen Williams replies to Feng-hsiung Hsu |url=http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/owenfeng.html |date=13 January 2000 |publisher=The Week in Chess |accessdate=11 May 2012 |postscript={{inconsistent citations}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729131411/http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/owenfeng.html |archivedate=29 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDeep Blue, with its capability of evaluating 200 million positions per second, was the fastest computer to face a world chess champion. Today, in computer-chess research and matches of world-class players against computers, the focus of play has often shifted to software [[:Category:Chess software|chess programs]], rather than using dedicated chess hardware. Modern chess programs like [[Houdini (chess)|Houdini]], [[Rybka]], [[Fritz (chess)|Deep Fritz]] or [[Junior (chess)|Deep Junior]] are more efficient than the programs during Deep Blue's era. In a November 2006 match between Deep Fritz and world chess champion [[Vladimir Kramnik]], the program ran on a computer system containing a dual-core [[List of Intel Xeon microprocessors#\"Woodcrest\" (65 nm)|Intel Xeon 5160]] [[Central processing unit|CPU]], capable of evaluating only 8 million positions per second, but searching to an average depth of 17 to 18 plies in the [[Chess middlegame|middlegame]] thanks to [[heuristic]]s; it won 4\u20132.<ref>{{Cite document |title=The last match man vs machine? |url=http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=3504 |date=23 November 2006 |publisher=ChessBase |work=English translation of Spiegel Article |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016172318/http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=3504 |archivedate=16 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6212076.stm |title=Chess champion loses to computer |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 December 2006 |accessdate=4 May 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231112514/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6212076.stm |archivedate=31 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[AlphaGo]]\n* [[Anti-computer tactics (gaming)|Anti-computer tactics]]\n* [[Deep Blue \u2013 Kasparov, 1996, Game 1]]\n* [[Deep Blue \u2013 Kasparov, 1997, Game 6]]\n* [[The Turk]]\n* [[Watson (computer)]]\n* [[X3D Fritz]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n|last=Hsu|first=Feng-hsiung|authorlink=Feng-hsiung Hsu\n|year=2002\n|title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the World Chess Champion\n|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-691-09065-3}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last1=Levy|given1=David|authorlink1=David Levy (chess player)\n|surname2=Newborn|given2=Monty\n|year=1991\n|title=How Computers Play Chess\n|publisher=Computer Science Press\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-7167-8121-2}}\n* {{Cite book\n| last = Campbell | first = Murray  | author-link=Murray Campbell\n| year = 1998\n| contribution=An Enjoyable Game\n| editor-last= Stork | editor-first= D. G.\n| title= HAL's Legacy: 2001's Computer as Dream and Reality\n| publisher= MIT Press | location= Cambridge, Massachusetts}}\n* {{Cite document\n| last = Syed | given1 = Omar\n| surname2 = Syed | given2 = Aamir\n| year = 2003\n| title= Arimaa \u2013 a New Game Designed to be Difficult for Computers\n| publisher=International Computer Games Association Journal 26: 138\u2013139\n}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite book\n|last=Newborn|first=Monty\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov versus Deep Blue: Computer Chess Comes of Age\n|publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media|Springer]]\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-387-94820-1}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last=King|first=Daniel|authorlink=Daniel King (chess player)\n|year=1997\n|title=Kasparov v. Deeper Blue: The Ultimate Man v. Machine Challenge\n|publisher=[[Batsford (publisher)|Batsford]]\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-7134-8322-9}}\n* {{cite book |last = Newborn |first = Monty\n |title = Deep Blue\n |url = https://archive.org/details/springer_10.1007-978-0-387-21790-1 |publisher = Springer\n |year = 2002\n |isbn =  0-387-95461-9}}\n* {{Cite journal | last1 = Campbell | first1 = M. | last2 = Hoane | doi = 10.1016/S0004-3702(01)00129-1 | first2 = A. J. | last3 = Hsu | first3 = F. H. | title = Deep Blue | journal = Artificial Intelligence | volume = 134 | issue = 1\u20132 | pages = 57\u201359 | year = 2002 | pmid =  | pmc = }}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Chessgames player|id=29912|name=Deep Blue}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070407074301/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/ IBM.com], IBM Research pages on Deep Blue\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080701232743/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/watch/html/c.shtml IBM.com], IBM page with the computer logs from the games\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20040406094751/http://www.chesscenter.com/twic/feng.html Chesscenter.com], Open letter from Feng-hsiung Hsu on the aborted rematch with Kasparov, ''[[The Week in Chess]]'' Magazine, issue 270, 10 January 2000\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090531080948/http://www.chesscenter.com/twic/owenfeng.html Chesscenter.com], Open Letter from Owen Williams (Gary Kasparov's manager), responding to Feng-hsiung Hsu, 13 January 2000\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20050520043104if_/http://sjeng.org:80/ftp/deepblue.pdf Sjeng.org], Deep Blue system described by Feng-hsiung Hsu, Murray Campbell and A. Joseph Hoane Jr. ([[PDF]])\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070701141111/http://www.chessclub.com/resources/articles/interview_crazybird1.html Chessclub.com], ICC Interview with Feng-Hsiung Hsu, an online interview with Hsu in 2002 (annotated)\n\n{{Chess}}\n{{IBM}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:History of chess]]\n[[Category:Chess computers]]\n[[Category:One-of-a-kind computers]]\n[[Category:IBM supercomputers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Chess-playing computer made by IBM}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2017}}\n{{Chess programming series}}\n[[File:Deep Blue.jpg|right|thumb|Deep Blue, at the [[Computer History Museum]]]]\n\n'''Deep Blue''' was a [[Computer chess|chess-playing computer]] developed by [[IBM]]. It is known for being the first computer chess-playing system to win both a chess game and a chess match against a reigning world champion under regular time controls.\n\nDeep Blue won its first game against a world champion on 10 February 1996, when it defeated [[Garry Kasparov]] in [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1|game one]] of a six-game match. However, [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]] won three and drew two of the following five games, defeating Deep Blue by a score of 4\u20132. Deep Blue was then heavily upgraded, and played Kasparov again in May 1997.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Mcphee|first=Michele|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/kasparov-deep-blues-losingchess-champ-rooke-article-1.762264|title=IBM's Deep Blue beats chess champion Garry Kasparov in 1997|date=May 10, 2015|work=[[NY Daily News]]|access-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live|last2=K.C. Baker|first2=|language=en|last3=Siemaszko|first3=Corky}}</ref> Deep Blue won [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6|game six]], thereby winning the six-game rematch 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd and becoming the first computer system to defeat a reigning world champion in a match under standard chess tournament time controls.<ref>{{cite magazine\n |title=Chess Bump: The triumphant teamwork of humans and computers\n |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2166000/\n |first=William\n |last=Saletan\n |author-link=William Saletan\n |magazine=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]\n |date=11 May 2007\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070513035007/http://www.slate.com/id/2166000/\n |archivedate=13 May 2007\n}}</ref> Kasparov accused IBM of [[cheating]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Hsu |first=Feng-Hsiung |date=2004 |edition=revised |title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the World Chess Champion |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WOk9DwAAQBAJ&pg=PR10 |publisher=Princeton University Press |page=Preface page x |isbn=9780691118185 }}</ref> and demanded a rematch. IBM refused and dismantled Deep Blue.\n\nDevelopment for Deep Blue began in 1985 with the [[ChipTest]] project at [[Carnegie Mellon University]]. This project eventually evolved into [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]], at which point the development team was hired by IBM.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Higgins|first=Chris|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/503178/brief-history-deep-blue-ibms-chess-computer|title=A Brief History of Deep Blue, IBM's Chess Computer|date=2017-07-29|work=[[Mental Floss]]|access-date=2017-08-03|url-status=live|language=en}}</ref> Grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]] was part of this development team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.computerhistory.org/chess/stl-431614f67f976/|title=Joel Benjamin playing a practice game with Deep Blue {{!}} Mastering the Game {{!}} Computer History Museum|website=www.computerhistory.org|access-date=2020-02-17}}</ref> The project evolved once more with the new name Deep Blue in 1989.\n\n== Origins ==\nThe project was started as [[ChipTest]] at [[Carnegie Mellon University]] by [[Feng-hsiung Hsu]], followed by its successor, [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]]. After their graduation from Carnegie Mellon, Hsu, [[Thomas Anantharaman]], and [[Murray Campbell]] from the Deep Thought team were hired by [[IBM Research]] to continue their quest to build a chess machine that could defeat the world champion.<ref name=\"Hsu-IBMHiring\">Hsu 2002, pp.92\u201395</ref> Hsu and Campbell joined IBM in autumn 1989, with Anantharaman following later.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.107</ref> Anantharaman subsequently left IBM for Wall Street and Arthur Joseph Hoane joined the team to perform programming tasks.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.132</ref> Jerry Brody, a long-time employee of IBM Research, was recruited for the team in 1990.<ref>{{cite web\n |author=IBM\n |title=Deep Blue \u2013 Overview\n |publisher=IBM Research\n |url=http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/meet/html/d.4.2.html\n |accessdate=19 August 2008\n |url-status=live\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081212221319/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/meet/html/d.4.2.html\n |archivedate=12 December 2008\n}}</ref>\nThe team was managed first by Randy Moulic, followed by Chung-Jen (C J) Tan.<ref>Hsu 2002, p.136</ref>\n\nAfter Deep Thought's 1989 match against Kasparov, IBM held a contest to rename the chess machine and it became \"Deep Blue\", a play on IBM's nickname, \"Big Blue\".<ref name=\"Hsu-DeepBlueName\">Hsu 2002, pp.126\u2013127</ref> After a scaled-down version of Deep Blue, Deep Blue Jr., played Grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]], Hsu and Campbell decided that Benjamin was the expert they were looking for to develop Deep Blue's [[Chess opening book (computers)|opening book]], and Benjamin was signed by IBM Research to assist with the preparations for Deep Blue's matches against Garry Kasparov.<ref>Hsu 2002, pp.160\u2013161, 174, 177, 193</ref>\n\nIn 1995 \"Deep Blue prototype\" (actually [[Deep Thought (chess computer)|Deep Thought]] II, renamed for PR reasons) played in the 8th [[World Computer Chess Championship]]. Deep Blue prototype played the computer program [[Power Chess|Wchess]] to a draw while Wchess was running on a [[personal computer]]. In round 5 Deep Blue prototype had the [[White and Black in chess|white pieces]] and lost to the computer program [[Fritz (chess)|Fritz]] 3 in 39 moves while Fritz was running on an Intel [[Pentium]] 90&nbsp;[[Megahertz|MHz]] personal computer. In the end of the championship Deep Blue prototype was tied for third place with the computer program Junior while Junior was running on a personal computer.<ref>[http://www.grappa.univ-lille3.fr/icga/tournament.php?id=29 Deep blue had white and lost to Fritz in 39 moves] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081007035001/http://www.grappa.univ-lille3.fr/icga/tournament.php?id=29 |date=7 October 2008 }}</ref>\n\n=== Design ===\nDeep Blue employed custom [[VLSI]] chips to execute the [[alpha\u2013beta pruning|alpha-beta search]] algorithm in [[parallel computing|parallel]],<ref>{{cite conference|last1=Hsu|first1=Feng-hsiung|last2=Campbell|first2=Murray|date=1995|title=Deep Blue System Overview|url=http://www.top-5000.nl/ps/Deep%20blue%20system%20overview.pdf|dead-url=|conference=|publisher=ACM|volume=|pages=240\u2013244|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181017043132if_/http://www.top-5000.nl/ps/Deep%20blue%20system%20overview.pdf|archive-date=October 17, 2018|via=|book-title=Proceedings of the 9th international conference on Supercomputing}}</ref> an example of [[GOFAI]] (Good Old-Fashioned Artificial Intelligence) rather than of [[deep learning]] which would come a decade later. It was a [[brute-force search]] approach, and one of its developers even denied that it was [[artificial intelligence]] at all.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/gilpress/2018/02/07/the-brute-force-of-deep-blue-and-deep-learning/ |title=The Brute Force of IBM Deep Blue And Google DeepMind |last=Press |first=Gil |date=7 February 2018 |website=forbes.com |access-date=12 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Deep Blue versus Kasparov ==\n{{Main|Deep Blue versus Garry Kasparov}}\n\nDeep Blue and Kasparov played each other on two occasions. The first match began on 10 February 1996, in which Deep Blue became the first machine to win [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1996, Game 1|a chess game against a reigning world champion]] ([[Garry Kasparov]]) under regular time controls. However, Kasparov won three and drew two of the following five games, beating Deep Blue by a score of 4\u20132 (wins count 1 point, draws count \u00bd point).  The match concluded on 17 February 1996.\n\nDeep Blue was then heavily upgraded (unofficially nicknamed \"Deeper Blue\")<ref>[http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game2/html/c.2.shtml IBM Research Game 2] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019031508/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/games/game2/html/c.2.shtml |date=19 October 2007 }}, Deep Blue [[IBM]]</ref> and played Kasparov again in May 1997, winning the six-game rematch 3\u00bd\u20132\u00bd, ending on 11 May. Deep Blue won the deciding [[Deep Blue versus Kasparov, 1997, Game 6|game six]] after Kasparov made a mistake in the opening, becoming the first computer system to defeat a reigning world champion in a match under standard chess tournament time controls.\n\nThe system derived its playing strength mainly from [[brute-force search|brute force]] computing power. It was a [[massively parallel]], [[IBM Scalable POWERparallel|RS/6000 SP Thin P2SC]]-based system with 30 nodes, with each node containing a 120&nbsp;MHz [[POWER2|P2SC]] [[microprocessor]], enhanced with 480 special purpose [[Very-large-scale integration|VLSI]] chess chips. Its chess playing program was written in [[C (programming language)|C]] and ran under the [[AIX operating system|AIX]] [[operating system]]. It was capable of evaluating 200 million positions per second, twice as fast as the 1996 version. In June 1997, Deep Blue was the 259th most powerful [[supercomputer]] according to the [[TOP500]] list, achieving 11.38 [[GFLOPS]] on the High-Performance [[LINPACK]] benchmark.<ref>[http://www.top500.org/list/1997/06/300 TOP500 Super Computer List \u2013 June 1997 (201\u2013300)] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090213103245/http://www.top500.org/list/1997/06/300 |date=13 February 2009 }} Top500.org</ref>\n\nThe Deep Blue chess computer that defeated [[Garry Kasparov|Kasparov]] in 1997 would typically search to a depth of between six and eight moves to a maximum of twenty or even more moves in some situations.<ref>Campbell 1998, p. 88.</ref> [[David Levy (chess player)|David Levy]] and [[Monty Newborn]] estimate that one additional [[Ply (game theory)|ply]] (half-move) increases the playing strength between 50 and 70 [[Elo rating system|Elo]] points.<ref>Levy & Newborn 1991, p. 192</ref>\n\n[[File:Kasparov Magath 1985 Hamburg-2.png|thumb|Kasparov in 1985]]\n\nDeep Blue's [[evaluation function]] was initially written in a generalized form, with many to-be-determined parameters (e.g. how important is a safe king position compared to a space advantage in the center, etc.). The optimal values for these parameters were then determined by the system itself, by analyzing thousands of master games. The evaluation function had been split into 8,000 parts, many of them designed for special positions. In the opening book there were over 4,000 positions and 700,000 [[Grandmaster (chess)|grandmaster]] games. The endgame database contained many six-piece endgames and five or fewer piece positions. Before the second match, the chess knowledge of the program was fine-tuned by grandmaster [[Joel Benjamin]]. The opening library was provided by grandmasters [[Miguel Illescas]], [[John Fedorowicz]], and [[Nick de Firmian]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/05/18/nyregion/what-deep-blue-learned-in-chess-school.html|title=What Deep Blue Learned in Chess School|last=Weber|first=Bruce|date=1997-05-18|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-07-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> When Kasparov requested that he be allowed to study other games that Deep Blue had played so as to better understand his opponent, IBM refused. However, Kasparov did study many popular PC games to become familiar with computer gameplay in general.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nWriter [[Nate Silver]] suggests that a [[Bug (software)|bug]] in Deep Blue's software led to a seemingly random move (the 44th in the first game of the second match) which Kasparov misattributed to \"superior intelligence\".<ref name=\"Roberts\">{{cite journal|last1=Roberts|first1=Jacob|title=Thinking Machines: The Search for Artificial Intelligence|journal=Distillations|date=2016|volume=2|issue=2|pages=14\u201323|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|accessdate=22 March 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180819152455/https://www.sciencehistory.org/distillations/magazine/thinking-machines-the-search-for-artificial-intelligence|archive-date=19 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Plumer\" /> Subsequently, Kasparov experienced a decline in performance due to anxiety in the following game.<ref name=\"Plumer\">{{cite web|last=Plumer |first=Brad |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/09/26/nate-silvers-the-signal-and-the-noise/ |title=Nate Silver's 'The Signal and the Noise' |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=26 September 2012 |accessdate=5 January 2014 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121109100324/http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/ezra-klein/wp/2012/09/26/nate-silvers-the-signal-and-the-noise/ |archivedate=9 November 2012 }}</ref> Kasparov rejects this interpretation.<ref>https://lccn.loc.gov/2017304768</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nComputer scientists believed that playing chess was a good measurement for the effectiveness of artificial intelligence, and by beating a world champion chess player, IBM showed that they had made significant progress.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/20-years-after-deep-blue-how-ai-has-advanced-since-conquering-chess/|title=20 Years after Deep Blue: How AI Has Advanced Since Conquering Chess|last=Greenemeier|first=Larry|work=Scientific American|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter the loss, Kasparov said that he sometimes saw deep intelligence and creativity in the machine's moves, suggesting that during the second game, human chess players had intervened on behalf of the machine, which would be a violation of the rules. IBM denied that it cheated, saying the only human intervention occurred between games. The rules provided for the developers to modify the program between games, an opportunity they said they used to shore up weaknesses in the computer's play that were revealed during the course of the match. Kasparov requested printouts of the machine's log files, but IBM refused, although the company later published the logs on the Internet.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080701232743/http://www.research.ibm.com/deepblue/watch/html/c.shtml Deep Blue the Match Replay the games]. [[IBM]].</ref> Kasparov demanded a rematch, but IBM refused and dismantled Deep Blue.<ref name=\"aboutMW\">[http://chess.about.com/library/weekly/aa05f04.htm 'Game Over' : Did IBM Cheat Kasparov?] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012234501/http://chess.about.com/library/weekly/aa05f04.htm |date=12 October 2007}}, by Mark Weeks, [[About.com]], June 2005.</ref> Owing to an insufficient sample of games between Deep Blue and officially rated chess players, a chess rating for Deep Blue was not established.{{citation needed|date = May 2012}}\n\nIn 2003 a [[documentary film]] was made that explored these claims. Entitled ''[[Game Over: Kasparov and the Machine]]'', the film interviewed some people who suggest that Deep Blue's victory was a ploy by IBM to boost its stock value.<ref name=\"aboutMW\" />\n\nOne of the cultural impacts of Deep Blue was the creation of a new game called [[Arimaa]] designed to be much more difficult for computers than chess.<ref>[http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/ibm100/us/en/icons/deepblue/impacts/ Deep Blue Cultural Impacts]. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330200410/http://www-03.ibm.com/ibm/history/ibm100/us/en/icons/deepblue/impacts/ |date=30 March 2014 }} [[IBM]].</ref>\n\nOne of the two racks that made up Deep Blue is on display at the [[National Museum of American History]] in their exhibit about the [[Information Age]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://americanhistory.si.edu/collections/search/object/nmah_1005331|title=Deep Blue Supercomputer Tower|website=National Museum of American History|language=en|access-date=2019-02-01}}</ref> the other rack appears at the [[Computer History Museum]] in the \"Artificial Intelligence and Robotics\" gallery of the Revolution exhibit.<ref>[http://www.computerhistory.org/chess/full_record.php?iid=art-43305f13ef377 Deep Blue II]. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703001709/http://www.computerhistory.org/chess/full_record.php?iid=art-43305f13ef377 |date=3 July 2013 }} [[Computer History Museum]] collections database. Retrieved 10 January 2014.</ref> Reports that Deep Blue was sold to [[United Airlines]] appear to originate from confusion between Deep Blue itself and other RS6000/SP2 systems.<ref>{{cite news |title=Deep Blue Skies: Ibm Helps Airline |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-12-07/business/9712051019_1_yield-management-airline-yield-management-systems |newspaper=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=7 December 1997 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130511053406/http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1997-12-07/business/9712051019_1_yield-management-airline-yield-management-systems |archivedate=11 May 2013 }}</ref>\n\n[[Feng-hsiung Hsu]] later claimed in his book ''Behind Deep Blue'' that he had the rights to use the Deep Blue design to build a bigger machine independently of IBM to take Kasparov's rematch offer, but Kasparov refused a rematch.<ref>{{Cite document |title=Owen Williams replies to Feng-hsiung Hsu |url=http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/owenfeng.html |date=13 January 2000 |publisher=The Week in Chess |accessdate=11 May 2012 |postscript={{inconsistent citations}} |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729131411/http://www.chess.co.uk/twic/owenfeng.html |archivedate=29 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\nDeep Blue, with its capability of evaluating 200 million positions per second, was the fastest computer to face a world chess champion. Today, in computer-chess research and matches of world-class players against computers, the focus of play has often shifted to software [[:Category:Chess software|chess programs]], rather than using dedicated chess hardware. Modern chess programs like [[Houdini (chess)|Houdini]], [[Rybka]], [[Fritz (chess)|Deep Fritz]] or [[Junior (chess)|Deep Junior]] are more efficient than the programs during Deep Blue's era. In a November 2006 match between Deep Fritz and world chess champion [[Vladimir Kramnik]], the program ran on a computer system containing a dual-core [[List of Intel Xeon microprocessors#\"Woodcrest\" (65 nm)|Intel Xeon 5160]] [[Central processing unit|CPU]], capable of evaluating only 8 million positions per second, but searching to an average depth of 17 to 18 plies in the [[Chess middlegame|middlegame]] thanks to [[heuristic]]s; it won 4\u20132.<ref>{{Cite document |title=The last match man vs machine? |url=http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=3504 |date=23 November 2006 |publisher=ChessBase |work=English translation of Spiegel Article |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016172318/http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=3504 |archivedate=16 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6212076.stm |title=Chess champion loses to computer |work=[[BBC News]] |date=5 December 2006 |accessdate=4 May 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071231112514/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6212076.stm |archivedate=31 December 2007 }}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Div col}}\n* [[AlphaGo]]\n* [[Anti-computer tactics (gaming)|Anti-computer tactics]]\n* [[Deep Blue \u2013 Kasparov, 1996, Game 1]]\n* [[Deep Blue \u2013 Kasparov, 1997, Game 6]]\n* [[The Turk]]\n* [[Watson (computer)]]\n* [[X3D Fritz]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* {{Cite book\n|last=Hsu|first=Feng-hsiung|authorlink=Feng-hsiung Hsu\n|year=2002\n|title=Behind Deep Blue: Building the Computer that Defeated the World Chess Champion\n|publisher=[[Princeton University Press]]\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-691-09065-3}}\n* {{Cite book\n|last1=Levy|given1=David|authorlink1=David Levy (chess player)\n|surname2=Newborn|given2=Monty\n|year=1991\n|title=How Computers Play Chess\n|publisher=Computer Science Press\n|ref=harv\n|isbn=0-7167-8121-2}}\n* {{Cite book\n| last = Campbell | first = Murray  | author-link=Murray Campbell\n| year = 1998\n| contribution=An Enjoyable Game\n| editor-last= Stork | editor-first= D. G.\n| title= HAL's Legacy: 2001's Computer as Dream and Reality\n| publisher= MIT Press | location= Cambridge, Massachusetts}}\n* {{Cite document\n| last = Syed | given1 = Omar\n| surname2 = Syed | give